87/// Returns the bitwidth of the given scalar or pointer type. For vector types,
88/// returns the element type's bitwidth.
89static unsigned getBitWidth(Type *Ty, const DataLayout &DL) {
90 if (unsigned BitWidth = Ty->getScalarSizeInBits())
91 return BitWidth;
92
93 return DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(Ty);
94}

98// Simplifying using an assume can only be done in a particular control-flow
99// context (the context instruction provides that context). If an assume and
100// the context instruction are not in the same block then the DT helps in
101// figuring out if we can use it.
102struct Query {
103 const DataLayout &DL;
104 AssumptionCache *AC;
105 const Instruction *CxtI;
106 const DominatorTree *DT;
107
108 // Unlike the other analyses, this may be a nullptr because not all clients
109 // provide it currently.
110 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE;
111
112 /// Set of assumptions that should be excluded from further queries.
113 /// This is because of the potential for mutual recursion to cause
114 /// computeKnownBits to repeatedly visit the same assume intrinsic. The
115 /// classic case of this is assume(x = y), which will attempt to determine
116 /// bits in x from bits in y, which will attempt to determine bits in y from
117 /// bits in x, etc. Regarding the mutual recursion, computeKnownBits can call
118 /// isKnownNonZero, which calls computeKnownBits and isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo
119 /// (all of which can call computeKnownBits), and so on.
120 std::array<const Value *, MaxDepth> Excluded;
121
122 /// If true, it is safe to use metadata during simplification.
123 InstrInfoQuery IIQ;
124
125 unsigned NumExcluded = 0;
126
127 Query(const DataLayout &DL, AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI,
128 const DominatorTree *DT, bool UseInstrInfo,
129 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE = nullptr)
130 : DL(DL), AC(AC), CxtI(CxtI), DT(DT), ORE(ORE), IIQ(UseInstrInfo) {}
131
132 Query(const Query &Q, const Value *NewExcl)
133 : DL(Q.DL), AC(Q.AC), CxtI(Q.CxtI), DT(Q.DT), ORE(Q.ORE), IIQ(Q.IIQ),
134 NumExcluded(Q.NumExcluded) {
135 Excluded = Q.Excluded;
136 Excluded[NumExcluded++] = NewExcl;
137 assert(NumExcluded <= Excluded.size());
138 }
139
140 bool isExcluded(const Value *Value) const {
141 if (NumExcluded == 0)
142 return false;
143 auto End = Excluded.begin() + NumExcluded;
144 return std::find(Excluded.begin(), End, Value) != End;
145 }
146};
147
148} // end anonymous namespace

150// Given the provided Value and, potentially, a context instruction, return
151// the preferred context instruction (if any).
152static const Instruction *safeCxtI(const Value *V, const Instruction *CxtI) {
153 // If we've been provided with a context instruction, then use that (provided
154 // it has been inserted).
155 if (CxtI && CxtI->getParent())
156 return CxtI;
157
158 // If the value is really an already-inserted instruction, then use that.
159 CxtI = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V);
160 if (CxtI && CxtI->getParent())
161 return CxtI;
162
163 return nullptr;
164}

191bool llvm::haveNoCommonBitsSet(const Value *LHS, const Value *RHS,
192 const DataLayout &DL, AssumptionCache *AC,
193 const Instruction *CxtI, const DominatorTree *DT,
194 bool UseInstrInfo) {
195 assert(LHS->getType() == RHS->getType() &&
196 "LHS and RHS should have the same type");
197 assert(LHS->getType()->isIntOrIntVectorTy() &&
198 "LHS and RHS should be integers");
199 // Look for an inverted mask: (X & ~M) op (Y & M).
200 Value *M;
201 if (match(LHS, m_c_And(m_Not(m_Value(M)), m_Value())) &&
202 match(RHS, m_c_And(m_Specific(M), m_Value())))
203 return true;
204 if (match(RHS, m_c_And(m_Not(m_Value(M)), m_Value())) &&
205 match(LHS, m_c_And(m_Specific(M), m_Value())))
206 return true;
207 IntegerType *IT = cast<IntegerType>(LHS->getType()->getScalarType());
208 KnownBits LHSKnown(IT->getBitWidth());
209 KnownBits RHSKnown(IT->getBitWidth());
210 computeKnownBits(LHS, LHSKnown, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT, nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
211 computeKnownBits(RHS, RHSKnown, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT, nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
212 return (LHSKnown.Zero | RHSKnown.Zero).isAllOnesValue();
213}

215bool llvm::isOnlyUsedInZeroEqualityComparison(const Instruction *CxtI) {
216 for (const User *U : CxtI->users()) {
217 if (const ICmpInst *IC = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(U))
218 if (IC->isEquality())
219 if (Constant *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(IC->getOperand(1)))
220 if (C->isNullValue())
221 continue;
222 return false;
223 }
224 return true;
225}

256bool llvm::isKnownPositive(const Value *V, const DataLayout &DL, unsigned Depth,
257 AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI,
258 const DominatorTree *DT, bool UseInstrInfo) {
259 if (auto *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(V))
260 return CI->getValue().isStrictlyPositive();
261
262 // TODO: We'd doing two recursive queries here. We should factor this such
263 // that only a single query is needed.
264 return isKnownNonNegative(V, DL, Depth, AC, CxtI, DT, UseInstrInfo) &&
265 isKnownNonZero(V, DL, Depth, AC, CxtI, DT, UseInstrInfo);
266}

287#define DEBUG_TAG(...) \
288 DEBUG_WITH_TYPE("infer-tag", dbgs() << __func__ << "(d=" << Depth \
289 << "): " << __VA_ARGS__; \
290 dbgs() << " -- "; V->dump())
291
292static bool isKnownUntaggedCapability(const Value *V, unsigned Depth,
293 const DataLayout *DL) {
294 assert(V && "No Value?");
295 assert(isCheriPointer(V->getType(), DL));
296 if (Depth >= MaxDepth) {
297 DEBUG_TAG("reached max depth -> false");
298 return false;
299 }
300 if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(V)) {
301 DEBUG_TAG("NULL pointer -> true");
302 return true; // NULL is always untagged
303 } else if (const auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(V)) {
304 switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
305 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_tag_clear:
306 DEBUG_TAG("ccleartag -> true");
307 return true;
308 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_offset_increment:
309 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_offset_set:
310 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_address_set:
311 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_perms_and:
312 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_flags_set:
313 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_bounds_set:
314 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_bounds_set_exact:
315 if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(II->getOperand(0))) {
316 DEBUG_TAG("modifying NULL cap -> true");
317 return true;
318 }
319 // Otherwise check if the source argument is known to be untagged:
320 return isKnownUntaggedCapability(II->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, DL);
321 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_from_ddc:
322 if (auto CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(II->getOperand(0))) {
323 DEBUG_TAG("CFromPtr on constant -> " << CI->isZeroValue());
324 return CI->isZeroValue(); // cfromdcc with zero returns NULL
325 }
326 DEBUG_TAG("CFromPtr on nonconst -> false");
327 return false; // We don't know if DDC is NULL -> could be tagged
328 default:
329 DEBUG_TAG("unknown intrinsic -> false");
330 // Any other intrinsic returning a capability could be a tagged value
331 return false;
332 }
333 } else if (const auto *GEPI = dyn_cast<GetElementPtrInst>(V)) {
334 // GEP on NULL has to be untagged
335 DEBUG_TAG("is GEP on NULL? -> "
336 << isa<ConstantPointerNull>(GEPI->getPointerOperand()));
337 return isa<ConstantPointerNull>(GEPI->getPointerOperand());
338 } else if (const auto *ITP = dyn_cast<IntToPtrInst>(V)) {
339 // IntToPtr returns untagged values in the pure capability ABI
340 bool Purecap = DL && isCheriPointer(DL->getAllocaAddrSpace(), DL);
341 DEBUG_TAG("is nonconst inttoptr in" << (Purecap ? "purecap" : "hybrid")
342 << " ABI -> " << Purecap);
343 bool IsZero = false;
344 if (auto Constant = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(ITP->getOperand(0)))
345 IsZero = Constant->isNullValue();
346 return Purecap || IsZero;
347 } else if (const auto *CE = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(V)) {
348 if (CE->getOpcode() == Instruction::CastOps::IntToPtr) {
349 // IntToPtr returns untagged values in the pure capability ABI
350 bool Purecap = DL && isCheriPointer(DL->getAllocaAddrSpace(), DL);
351 DEBUG_TAG("is constant inttoptr in" << (Purecap ? "purecap" : "hybrid")
352 << " ABI -> " << Purecap);
353 return Purecap;
354 }
355 DEBUG_TAG("unknown constantexpr -> false");
356 return false;
357 }
358 DEBUG_TAG("unknown value -> false");
359 // Anything else could be tagged (what about GEP on NULL?)
360 return false;
361}

392static void computeKnownBitsAddSub(bool Add, const Value *Op0, const Value *Op1,
393 bool NSW,
394 KnownBits &KnownOut, KnownBits &Known2,
395 unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
396 unsigned BitWidth = KnownOut.getBitWidth();
397
398 // If an initial sequence of bits in the result is not needed, the
399 // corresponding bits in the operands are not needed.
400 KnownBits LHSKnown(BitWidth);
401 computeKnownBits(Op0, LHSKnown, Depth + 1, Q);
402 computeKnownBits(Op1, Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
403
404 KnownOut = KnownBits::computeForAddSub(Add, NSW, LHSKnown, Known2);
405}
406
407static void computeKnownBitsMul(const Value *Op0, const Value *Op1, bool NSW,
408 KnownBits &Known, KnownBits &Known2,
409 unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
410 unsigned BitWidth = Known.getBitWidth();
411 computeKnownBits(Op1, Known, Depth + 1, Q);
412 computeKnownBits(Op0, Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
413
414 bool isKnownNegative = false;
415 bool isKnownNonNegative = false;
416 // If the multiplication is known not to overflow, compute the sign bit.
417 if (NSW) {
418 if (Op0 == Op1) {
419 // The product of a number with itself is non-negative.
420 isKnownNonNegative = true;
421 } else {
422 bool isKnownNonNegativeOp1 = Known.isNonNegative();
423 bool isKnownNonNegativeOp0 = Known2.isNonNegative();
424 bool isKnownNegativeOp1 = Known.isNegative();
425 bool isKnownNegativeOp0 = Known2.isNegative();
426 // The product of two numbers with the same sign is non-negative.
427 isKnownNonNegative = (isKnownNegativeOp1 && isKnownNegativeOp0) ||
428 (isKnownNonNegativeOp1 && isKnownNonNegativeOp0);
429 // The product of a negative number and a non-negative number is either
430 // negative or zero.
431 if (!isKnownNonNegative)
432 isKnownNegative = (isKnownNegativeOp1 && isKnownNonNegativeOp0 &&
433 isKnownNonZero(Op0, Depth, Q)) ||
434 (isKnownNegativeOp0 && isKnownNonNegativeOp1 &&
435 isKnownNonZero(Op1, Depth, Q));
436 }
437 }
438
439 assert(!Known.hasConflict() && !Known2.hasConflict());
440 // Compute a conservative estimate for high known-0 bits.
441 unsigned LeadZ = std::max(Known.countMinLeadingZeros() +
442 Known2.countMinLeadingZeros(),
443 BitWidth) - BitWidth;
444 LeadZ = std::min(LeadZ, BitWidth);
445
446 // The result of the bottom bits of an integer multiply can be
447 // inferred by looking at the bottom bits of both operands and
448 // multiplying them together.
449 // We can infer at least the minimum number of known trailing bits
450 // of both operands. Depending on number of trailing zeros, we can
451 // infer more bits, because (a*b) <=> ((a/m) * (b/n)) * (m*n) assuming
452 // a and b are divisible by m and n respectively.
453 // We then calculate how many of those bits are inferrable and set
454 // the output. For example, the i8 mul:
455 // a = XXXX1100 (12)
456 // b = XXXX1110 (14)
457 // We know the bottom 3 bits are zero since the first can be divided by
458 // 4 and the second by 2, thus having ((12/4) * (14/2)) * (2*4).
459 // Applying the multiplication to the trimmed arguments gets:
460 // XX11 (3)
461 // X111 (7)
462 // -------
463 // XX11
464 // XX11
465 // XX11
466 // XX11
467 // -------
468 // XXXXX01
469 // Which allows us to infer the 2 LSBs. Since we're multiplying the result
470 // by 8, the bottom 3 bits will be 0, so we can infer a total of 5 bits.
471 // The proof for this can be described as:
472 // Pre: (C1 >= 0) && (C1 < (1 << C5)) && (C2 >= 0) && (C2 < (1 << C6)) &&
473 // (C7 == (1 << (umin(countTrailingZeros(C1), C5) +
474 // umin(countTrailingZeros(C2), C6) +
475 // umin(C5 - umin(countTrailingZeros(C1), C5),
476 // C6 - umin(countTrailingZeros(C2), C6)))) - 1)
477 // %aa = shl i8 %a, C5
478 // %bb = shl i8 %b, C6
479 // %aaa = or i8 %aa, C1
480 // %bbb = or i8 %bb, C2
481 // %mul = mul i8 %aaa, %bbb
482 // %mask = and i8 %mul, C7
483 // =>
484 // %mask = i8 ((C1*C2)&C7)
485 // Where C5, C6 describe the known bits of %a, %b
486 // C1, C2 describe the known bottom bits of %a, %b.
487 // C7 describes the mask of the known bits of the result.
488 APInt Bottom0 = Known.One;
489 APInt Bottom1 = Known2.One;
490
491 // How many times we'd be able to divide each argument by 2 (shr by 1).
492 // This gives us the number of trailing zeros on the multiplication result.
493 unsigned TrailBitsKnown0 = (Known.Zero | Known.One).countTrailingOnes();
494 unsigned TrailBitsKnown1 = (Known2.Zero | Known2.One).countTrailingOnes();
495 unsigned TrailZero0 = Known.countMinTrailingZeros();
496 unsigned TrailZero1 = Known2.countMinTrailingZeros();
497 unsigned TrailZ = TrailZero0 + TrailZero1;
498
499 // Figure out the fewest known-bits operand.
500 unsigned SmallestOperand = std::min(TrailBitsKnown0 - TrailZero0,
501 TrailBitsKnown1 - TrailZero1);
502 unsigned ResultBitsKnown = std::min(SmallestOperand + TrailZ, BitWidth);
503
504 APInt BottomKnown = Bottom0.getLoBits(TrailBitsKnown0) *
505 Bottom1.getLoBits(TrailBitsKnown1);
506
507 Known.resetAll();
508 Known.Zero.setHighBits(LeadZ);
509 Known.Zero |= (~BottomKnown).getLoBits(ResultBitsKnown);
510 Known.One |= BottomKnown.getLoBits(ResultBitsKnown);
511
512 // Only make use of no-wrap flags if we failed to compute the sign bit
513 // directly. This matters if the multiplication always overflows, in
514 // which case we prefer to follow the result of the direct computation,
515 // though as the program is invoking undefined behaviour we can choose
516 // whatever we like here.
517 if (isKnownNonNegative && !Known.isNegative())
518 Known.makeNonNegative();
519 else if (isKnownNegative && !Known.isNonNegative())
520 Known.makeNegative();
521}

523void llvm::computeKnownBitsFromRangeMetadata(const MDNode &Ranges,
524 KnownBits &Known) {
525 unsigned BitWidth = Known.getBitWidth();
526 unsigned NumRanges = Ranges.getNumOperands() / 2;
527 assert(NumRanges >= 1);
528
529 Known.Zero.setAllBits();
530 Known.One.setAllBits();
531
532 for (unsigned i = 0; i < NumRanges; ++i) {
533 ConstantInt *Lower =
534 mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(Ranges.getOperand(2 * i + 0));
535 ConstantInt *Upper =
536 mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(Ranges.getOperand(2 * i + 1));
537 ConstantRange Range(Lower->getValue(), Upper->getValue());
538
539 // The first CommonPrefixBits of all values in Range are equal.
540 unsigned CommonPrefixBits =
541 (Range.getUnsignedMax() ^ Range.getUnsignedMin()).countLeadingZeros();
542
543 APInt Mask = APInt::getHighBitsSet(BitWidth, CommonPrefixBits);
544 Known.One &= Range.getUnsignedMax() & Mask;
545 Known.Zero &= ~Range.getUnsignedMax() & Mask;
546 }
547}

549static bool isEphemeralValueOf(const Instruction *I, const Value *E) {
550 SmallVector<const Value *, 16> WorkSet(1, I);
551 SmallPtrSet<const Value *, 32> Visited;
552 SmallPtrSet<const Value *, 16> EphValues;
553
554 // The instruction defining an assumption's condition itself is always
555 // considered ephemeral to that assumption (even if it has other
556 // non-ephemeral users). See r246696's test case for an example.
557 if (is_contained(I->operands(), E))
558 return true;
559
560 while (!WorkSet.empty()) {
561 const Value *V = WorkSet.pop_back_val();
562 if (!Visited.insert(V).second)
563 continue;
564
565 // If all uses of this value are ephemeral, then so is this value.
566 if (llvm::all_of(V->users(), [&](const User *U) {
567 return EphValues.count(U);
568 })) {
569 if (V == E)
570 return true;
571
572 if (V == I || isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(V)) {
573 EphValues.insert(V);
574 if (const User *U = dyn_cast<User>(V))
575 for (User::const_op_iterator J = U->op_begin(), JE = U->op_end();
576 J != JE; ++J)
577 WorkSet.push_back(*J);
578 }
579 }
580 }
581
582 return false;
583}

585// Is this an intrinsic that cannot be speculated but also cannot trap?
586bool llvm::isAssumeLikeIntrinsic(const Instruction *I) {
587 if (const CallInst *CI = dyn_cast<CallInst>(I))
588 if (Function *F = CI->getCalledFunction())
589 switch (F->getIntrinsicID()) {
590 default: break;
591 // FIXME: This list is repeated from NoTTI::getIntrinsicCost.
592 case Intrinsic::assume:
593 case Intrinsic::sideeffect:
594 case Intrinsic::dbg_declare:
595 case Intrinsic::dbg_value:
596 case Intrinsic::dbg_label:
597 case Intrinsic::invariant_start:
598 case Intrinsic::invariant_end:
599 case Intrinsic::lifetime_start:
600 case Intrinsic::lifetime_end:
601 case Intrinsic::objectsize:
602 case Intrinsic::ptr_annotation:
603 case Intrinsic::var_annotation:
604 return true;
605 }
606
607 return false;
608}
609
610bool llvm::isValidAssumeForContext(const Instruction *Inv,
611 const Instruction *CxtI,
612 const DominatorTree *DT) {
613 // There are two restrictions on the use of an assume:
614 // 1. The assume must dominate the context (or the control flow must
615 // reach the assume whenever it reaches the context).
616 // 2. The context must not be in the assume's set of ephemeral values
617 // (otherwise we will use the assume to prove that the condition
618 // feeding the assume is trivially true, thus causing the removal of
619 // the assume).
620
621 if (DT) {
622 if (DT->dominates(Inv, CxtI))
623 return true;
624 } else if (Inv->getParent() == CxtI->getParent()->getSinglePredecessor()) {
625 // We don't have a DT, but this trivially dominates.
626 return true;
627 }
628
629 // With or without a DT, the only remaining case we will check is if the
630 // instructions are in the same BB. Give up if that is not the case.
631 if (Inv->getParent() != CxtI->getParent())
632 return false;
633
634 // If we have a dom tree, then we now know that the assume doesn't dominate
635 // the other instruction. If we don't have a dom tree then we can check if
636 // the assume is first in the BB.
637 if (!DT) {
638 // Search forward from the assume until we reach the context (or the end
639 // of the block); the common case is that the assume will come first.
640 for (auto I = std::next(BasicBlock::const_iterator(Inv)),
641 IE = Inv->getParent()->end(); I != IE; ++I)
642 if (&*I == CxtI)
643 return true;
644 }
645
646 // The context comes first, but they're both in the same block. Make sure
647 // there is nothing in between that might interrupt the control flow.
648 for (BasicBlock::const_iterator I =
649 std::next(BasicBlock::const_iterator(CxtI)), IE(Inv);
650 I != IE; ++I)
651 if (!isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(&*I) && !isAssumeLikeIntrinsic(&*I))
652 return false;
653
654 return !isEphemeralValueOf(Inv, CxtI);
655}
656
657static void computeKnownBitsFromAssume(const Value *V, KnownBits &Known,
658 unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
659 // Use of assumptions is context-sensitive. If we don't have a context, we
660 // cannot use them!
661 if (!Q.AC || !Q.CxtI)
662 return;
663
664 unsigned BitWidth = Known.getBitWidth();
665
666 // Note that the patterns below need to be kept in sync with the code
667 // in AssumptionCache::updateAffectedValues.
668
669 for (auto &AssumeVH : Q.AC->assumptionsFor(V)) {
670 if (!AssumeVH)
671 continue;
672 CallInst *I = cast<CallInst>(AssumeVH);
673 assert(I->getParent()->getParent() == Q.CxtI->getParent()->getParent() &&
674 "Got assumption for the wrong function!");
675 if (Q.isExcluded(I))
676 continue;
677
678 // Warning: This loop can end up being somewhat performance sensitive.
679 // We're running this loop for once for each value queried resulting in a
680 // runtime of ~O(#assumes * #values).
681
682 assert(I->getCalledFunction()->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::assume &&
683 "must be an assume intrinsic");
684
685 Value *Arg = I->getArgOperand(0);
686
687 if (Arg == V && isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
688 assert(BitWidth == 1 && "assume operand is not i1?");
689 Known.setAllOnes();
690 return;
691 }
692 if (match(Arg, m_Not(m_Specific(V))) &&
693 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
694 assert(BitWidth == 1 && "assume operand is not i1?");
695 Known.setAllZero();
696 return;
697 }
698
699 // The remaining tests are all recursive, so bail out if we hit the limit.
700 if (Depth == MaxDepth)
701 continue;
702
703 ICmpInst *Cmp = dyn_cast<ICmpInst>(Arg);
704 if (!Cmp)
705 continue;
706
707 Value *A, *B;
708 auto m_V = m_CombineOr(m_Specific(V), m_PtrToInt(m_Specific(V)));
709
710 CmpInst::Predicate Pred;
711 uint64_t C;
712 switch (Cmp->getPredicate()) {
713 default:
714 break;
715 case ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ:
716 // assume(v = a)
717 if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
718 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
719 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
720 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
721 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero;
722 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One;
723 // assume(v & b = a)
724 } else if (match(Cmp,
725 m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_c_And(m_V, m_Value(B)), m_Value(A))) &&
726 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
727 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
728 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
729 KnownBits MaskKnown(BitWidth);
730 computeKnownBits(B, MaskKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
731
732 // For those bits in the mask that are known to be one, we can propagate
733 // known bits from the RHS to V.
734 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero & MaskKnown.One;
735 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One & MaskKnown.One;
736 // assume(~(v & b) = a)
737 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Not(m_c_And(m_V, m_Value(B))),
738 m_Value(A))) &&
739 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
740 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
741 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
742 KnownBits MaskKnown(BitWidth);
743 computeKnownBits(B, MaskKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
744
745 // For those bits in the mask that are known to be one, we can propagate
746 // inverted known bits from the RHS to V.
747 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.One & MaskKnown.One;
748 Known.One |= RHSKnown.Zero & MaskKnown.One;
749 // assume(v | b = a)
750 } else if (match(Cmp,
751 m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_c_Or(m_V, m_Value(B)), m_Value(A))) &&
752 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
753 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
754 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
755 KnownBits BKnown(BitWidth);
756 computeKnownBits(B, BKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
757
758 // For those bits in B that are known to be zero, we can propagate known
759 // bits from the RHS to V.
760 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero & BKnown.Zero;
761 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One & BKnown.Zero;
762 // assume(~(v | b) = a)
763 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Not(m_c_Or(m_V, m_Value(B))),
764 m_Value(A))) &&
765 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
766 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
767 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
768 KnownBits BKnown(BitWidth);
769 computeKnownBits(B, BKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
770
771 // For those bits in B that are known to be zero, we can propagate
772 // inverted known bits from the RHS to V.
773 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.One & BKnown.Zero;
774 Known.One |= RHSKnown.Zero & BKnown.Zero;
775 // assume(v ^ b = a)
776 } else if (match(Cmp,
777 m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_c_Xor(m_V, m_Value(B)), m_Value(A))) &&
778 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
779 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
780 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
781 KnownBits BKnown(BitWidth);
782 computeKnownBits(B, BKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
783
784 // For those bits in B that are known to be zero, we can propagate known
785 // bits from the RHS to V. For those bits in B that are known to be one,
786 // we can propagate inverted known bits from the RHS to V.
787 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero & BKnown.Zero;
788 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One & BKnown.Zero;
789 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.One & BKnown.One;
790 Known.One |= RHSKnown.Zero & BKnown.One;
791 // assume(~(v ^ b) = a)
792 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Not(m_c_Xor(m_V, m_Value(B))),
793 m_Value(A))) &&
794 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
795 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
796 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
797 KnownBits BKnown(BitWidth);
798 computeKnownBits(B, BKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
799
800 // For those bits in B that are known to be zero, we can propagate
801 // inverted known bits from the RHS to V. For those bits in B that are
802 // known to be one, we can propagate known bits from the RHS to V.
803 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.One & BKnown.Zero;
804 Known.One |= RHSKnown.Zero & BKnown.Zero;
805 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero & BKnown.One;
806 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One & BKnown.One;
807 // assume(v << c = a)
808 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Shl(m_V, m_ConstantInt(C)),
809 m_Value(A))) &&
810 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT) && C < BitWidth) {
811 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
812 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
813 // For those bits in RHS that are known, we can propagate them to known
814 // bits in V shifted to the right by C.
815 RHSKnown.Zero.lshrInPlace(C);
816 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero;
817 RHSKnown.One.lshrInPlace(C);
818 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One;
819 // assume(~(v << c) = a)
820 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Not(m_Shl(m_V, m_ConstantInt(C))),
821 m_Value(A))) &&
822 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT) && C < BitWidth) {
823 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
824 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
825 // For those bits in RHS that are known, we can propagate them inverted
826 // to known bits in V shifted to the right by C.
827 RHSKnown.One.lshrInPlace(C);
828 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.One;
829 RHSKnown.Zero.lshrInPlace(C);
830 Known.One |= RHSKnown.Zero;
831 // assume(v >> c = a)
832 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Shr(m_V, m_ConstantInt(C)),
833 m_Value(A))) &&
834 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT) && C < BitWidth) {
835 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
836 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
837 // For those bits in RHS that are known, we can propagate them to known
838 // bits in V shifted to the right by C.
839 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.Zero << C;
840 Known.One |= RHSKnown.One << C;
841 // assume(~(v >> c) = a)
842 } else if (match(Cmp, m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Not(m_Shr(m_V, m_ConstantInt(C))),
843 m_Value(A))) &&
844 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT) && C < BitWidth) {
845 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
846 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
847 // For those bits in RHS that are known, we can propagate them inverted
848 // to known bits in V shifted to the right by C.
849 Known.Zero |= RHSKnown.One << C;
850 Known.One |= RHSKnown.Zero << C;
851 }
852 break;
853 case ICmpInst::ICMP_SGE:
854 // assume(v >=_s c) where c is non-negative
855 if (match(Cmp, m_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
856 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
857 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
858 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth + 1, Query(Q, I));
859
860 if (RHSKnown.isNonNegative()) {
861 // We know that the sign bit is zero.
862 Known.makeNonNegative();
863 }
864 }
865 break;
866 case ICmpInst::ICMP_SGT:
867 // assume(v >_s c) where c is at least -1.
868 if (match(Cmp, m_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
869 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
870 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
871 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth + 1, Query(Q, I));
872
873 if (RHSKnown.isAllOnes() || RHSKnown.isNonNegative()) {
874 // We know that the sign bit is zero.
875 Known.makeNonNegative();
876 }
877 }
878 break;
879 case ICmpInst::ICMP_SLE:
880 // assume(v <=_s c) where c is negative
881 if (match(Cmp, m_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
882 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
883 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
884 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth + 1, Query(Q, I));
885
886 if (RHSKnown.isNegative()) {
887 // We know that the sign bit is one.
888 Known.makeNegative();
889 }
890 }
891 break;
892 case ICmpInst::ICMP_SLT:
893 // assume(v <_s c) where c is non-positive
894 if (match(Cmp, m_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
895 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
896 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
897 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
898
899 if (RHSKnown.isZero() || RHSKnown.isNegative()) {
900 // We know that the sign bit is one.
901 Known.makeNegative();
902 }
903 }
904 break;
905 case ICmpInst::ICMP_ULE:
906 // assume(v <=_u c)
907 if (match(Cmp, m_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
908 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
909 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
910 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
911
912 // Whatever high bits in c are zero are known to be zero.
913 Known.Zero.setHighBits(RHSKnown.countMinLeadingZeros());
914 }
915 break;
916 case ICmpInst::ICMP_ULT:
917 // assume(v <_u c)
918 if (match(Cmp, m_ICmp(Pred, m_V, m_Value(A))) &&
919 isValidAssumeForContext(I, Q.CxtI, Q.DT)) {
920 KnownBits RHSKnown(BitWidth);
921 computeKnownBits(A, RHSKnown, Depth+1, Query(Q, I));
922
923 // If the RHS is known zero, then this assumption must be wrong (nothing
924 // is unsigned less than zero). Signal a conflict and get out of here.
925 if (RHSKnown.isZero()) {
926 Known.Zero.setAllBits();
927 Known.One.setAllBits();
928 break;
929 }
930
931 // Whatever high bits in c are zero are known to be zero (if c is a power
932 // of 2, then one more).
933 if (isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(A, false, Depth + 1, Query(Q, I)))
934 Known.Zero.setHighBits(RHSKnown.countMinLeadingZeros() + 1);
935 else
936 Known.Zero.setHighBits(RHSKnown.countMinLeadingZeros());
937 }
938 break;
939 }
940 }
941
942 // If assumptions conflict with each other or previous known bits, then we
943 // have a logical fallacy. It's possible that the assumption is not reachable,
944 // so this isn't a real bug. On the other hand, the program may have undefined
945 // behavior, or we might have a bug in the compiler. We can't assert/crash, so
946 // clear out the known bits, try to warn the user, and hope for the best.
947 if (Known.Zero.intersects(Known.One)) {
948 Known.resetAll();
949
950 if (Q.ORE)
951 Q.ORE->emit([&]() {
952 auto *CxtI = const_cast<Instruction *>(Q.CxtI);
953 return OptimizationRemarkAnalysis("value-tracking", "BadAssumption",
954 CxtI)
955 << "Detected conflicting code assumptions. Program may "
956 "have undefined behavior, or compiler may have "
957 "internal error.";
958 });
959 }
960}
961
962/// Compute known bits from a shift operator, including those with a
963/// non-constant shift amount. Known is the output of this function. Known2 is a
964/// pre-allocated temporary with the same bit width as Known. KZF and KOF are
965/// operator-specific functions that, given the known-zero or known-one bits
966/// respectively, and a shift amount, compute the implied known-zero or
967/// known-one bits of the shift operator's result respectively for that shift
968/// amount. The results from calling KZF and KOF are conservatively combined for
969/// all permitted shift amounts.
970static void computeKnownBitsFromShiftOperator(
971 const Operator *I, KnownBits &Known, KnownBits &Known2,
972 unsigned Depth, const Query &Q,
973 function_ref<APInt(const APInt &, unsigned)> KZF,
974 function_ref<APInt(const APInt &, unsigned)> KOF) {
975 unsigned BitWidth = Known.getBitWidth();
976
977 if (auto *SA = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1))) {
978 unsigned ShiftAmt = SA->getLimitedValue(BitWidth-1);
979
980 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
981 Known.Zero = KZF(Known.Zero, ShiftAmt);
982 Known.One = KOF(Known.One, ShiftAmt);
983 // If the known bits conflict, this must be an overflowing left shift, so
984 // the shift result is poison. We can return anything we want. Choose 0 for
985 // the best folding opportunity.
986 if (Known.hasConflict())
987 Known.setAllZero();
988
989 return;
990 }
991
992 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
993
994 // If the shift amount could be greater than or equal to the bit-width of the
995 // LHS, the value could be poison, but bail out because the check below is
996 // expensive. TODO: Should we just carry on?
997 if ((~Known.Zero).uge(BitWidth)) {
998 Known.resetAll();
999 return;
1000 }
1001
1002 // Note: We cannot use Known.Zero.getLimitedValue() here, because if
1003 // BitWidth > 64 and any upper bits are known, we'll end up returning the
1004 // limit value (which implies all bits are known).
1005 uint64_t ShiftAmtKZ = Known.Zero.zextOrTrunc(64).getZExtValue();
1006 uint64_t ShiftAmtKO = Known.One.zextOrTrunc(64).getZExtValue();
1007
1008 // It would be more-clearly correct to use the two temporaries for this
1009 // calculation. Reusing the APInts here to prevent unnecessary allocations.
1010 Known.resetAll();
1011
1012 // If we know the shifter operand is nonzero, we can sometimes infer more
1013 // known bits. However this is expensive to compute, so be lazy about it and
1014 // only compute it when absolutely necessary.
1015 Optional<bool> ShifterOperandIsNonZero;
1016
1017 // Early exit if we can't constrain any well-defined shift amount.
1018 if (!(ShiftAmtKZ & (PowerOf2Ceil(BitWidth) - 1)) &&
1019 !(ShiftAmtKO & (PowerOf2Ceil(BitWidth) - 1))) {
1020 ShifterOperandIsNonZero = isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
1021 if (!*ShifterOperandIsNonZero)
1022 return;
1023 }
1024
1025 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1026
1027 Known.Zero.setAllBits();
1028 Known.One.setAllBits();
1029 for (unsigned ShiftAmt = 0; ShiftAmt < BitWidth; ++ShiftAmt) {
1030 // Combine the shifted known input bits only for those shift amounts
1031 // compatible with its known constraints.
1032 if ((ShiftAmt & ~ShiftAmtKZ) != ShiftAmt)
1033 continue;
1034 if ((ShiftAmt | ShiftAmtKO) != ShiftAmt)
1035 continue;
1036 // If we know the shifter is nonzero, we may be able to infer more known
1037 // bits. This check is sunk down as far as possible to avoid the expensive
1038 // call to isKnownNonZero if the cheaper checks above fail.
1039 if (ShiftAmt == 0) {
1040 if (!ShifterOperandIsNonZero.hasValue())
1041 ShifterOperandIsNonZero =
1042 isKnownNonZero(I->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
1043 if (*ShifterOperandIsNonZero)
1044 continue;
1045 }
1046
1047 Known.Zero &= KZF(Known2.Zero, ShiftAmt);
1048 Known.One &= KOF(Known2.One, ShiftAmt);
1049 }
1050
1051 // If the known bits conflict, the result is poison. Return a 0 and hope the
1052 // caller can further optimize that.
1053 if (Known.hasConflict())
1054 Known.setAllZero();
1055}
1056
1057static void computeKnownBitsFromOperator(const Operator *I, KnownBits &Known,
1058 unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
1059 unsigned BitWidth = Known.getBitWidth();
1060
1061 KnownBits Known2(Known);
1062 switch (I->getOpcode()) {
1063 default: break;
1064 case Instruction::Load:
1065 if (MDNode *MD =
1066 Q.IIQ.getMetadata(cast<LoadInst>(I), LLVMContext::MD_range))
1067 computeKnownBitsFromRangeMetadata(*MD, Known);
1068 break;
1069 case Instruction::And: {
1070 // If either the LHS or the RHS are Zero, the result is zero.
1071 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1072 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1073
1074 // Output known-1 bits are only known if set in both the LHS & RHS.
1075 Known.One &= Known2.One;
1076 // Output known-0 are known to be clear if zero in either the LHS | RHS.
1077 Known.Zero |= Known2.Zero;
1078
1079 // and(x, add (x, -1)) is a common idiom that always clears the low bit;
1080 // here we handle the more general case of adding any odd number by
1081 // matching the form add(x, add(x, y)) where y is odd.
1082 // TODO: This could be generalized to clearing any bit set in y where the
1083 // following bit is known to be unset in y.
1084 Value *X = nullptr, *Y = nullptr;
1085 if (!Known.Zero[0] && !Known.One[0] &&
1086 match(I, m_c_BinOp(m_Value(X), m_Add(m_Deferred(X), m_Value(Y))))) {
1087 Known2.resetAll();
1088 computeKnownBits(Y, Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1089 if (Known2.countMinTrailingOnes() > 0)
1090 Known.Zero.setBit(0);
1091 }
1092 break;
1093 }
1094 case Instruction::Or:
1095 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1096 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1097
1098 // Output known-0 bits are only known if clear in both the LHS & RHS.
1099 Known.Zero &= Known2.Zero;
1100 // Output known-1 are known to be set if set in either the LHS | RHS.
1101 Known.One |= Known2.One;
1102 break;
1103 case Instruction::Xor: {
1104 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1105 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1106
1107 // Output known-0 bits are known if clear or set in both the LHS & RHS.
1108 APInt KnownZeroOut = (Known.Zero & Known2.Zero) | (Known.One & Known2.One);
1109 // Output known-1 are known to be set if set in only one of the LHS, RHS.
1110 Known.One = (Known.Zero & Known2.One) | (Known.One & Known2.Zero);
1111 Known.Zero = std::move(KnownZeroOut);
1112 break;
1113 }
1114 case Instruction::Mul: {
1115 bool NSW = Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(I));
1116 computeKnownBitsMul(I->getOperand(0), I->getOperand(1), NSW, Known,
1117 Known2, Depth, Q);
1118 break;
1119 }
1120 case Instruction::UDiv: {
1121 // For the purposes of computing leading zeros we can conservatively
1122 // treat a udiv as a logical right shift by the power of 2 known to
1123 // be less than the denominator.
1124 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1125 unsigned LeadZ = Known2.countMinLeadingZeros();
1126
1127 Known2.resetAll();
1128 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1129 unsigned RHSMaxLeadingZeros = Known2.countMaxLeadingZeros();
1130 if (RHSMaxLeadingZeros != BitWidth)
1131 LeadZ = std::min(BitWidth, LeadZ + BitWidth - RHSMaxLeadingZeros - 1);
1132
1133 Known.Zero.setHighBits(LeadZ);
1134 break;
1135 }
1136 case Instruction::Select: {
1137 const Value *LHS, *RHS;
1138 SelectPatternFlavor SPF = matchSelectPattern(I, LHS, RHS).Flavor;
1139 if (SelectPatternResult::isMinOrMax(SPF)) {
1140 computeKnownBits(RHS, Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1141 computeKnownBits(LHS, Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1142 } else {
1143 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(2), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1144 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1145 }
1146
1147 unsigned MaxHighOnes = 0;
1148 unsigned MaxHighZeros = 0;
1149 if (SPF == SPF_SMAX) {
1150 // If both sides are negative, the result is negative.
1151 if (Known.isNegative() && Known2.isNegative())
1152 // We can derive a lower bound on the result by taking the max of the
1153 // leading one bits.
1154 MaxHighOnes =
1155 std::max(Known.countMinLeadingOnes(), Known2.countMinLeadingOnes());
1156 // If either side is non-negative, the result is non-negative.
1157 else if (Known.isNonNegative() || Known2.isNonNegative())
1158 MaxHighZeros = 1;
1159 } else if (SPF == SPF_SMIN) {
1160 // If both sides are non-negative, the result is non-negative.
1161 if (Known.isNonNegative() && Known2.isNonNegative())
1162 // We can derive an upper bound on the result by taking the max of the
1163 // leading zero bits.
1164 MaxHighZeros = std::max(Known.countMinLeadingZeros(),
1165 Known2.countMinLeadingZeros());
1166 // If either side is negative, the result is negative.
1167 else if (Known.isNegative() || Known2.isNegative())
1168 MaxHighOnes = 1;
1169 } else if (SPF == SPF_UMAX) {
1170 // We can derive a lower bound on the result by taking the max of the
1171 // leading one bits.
1172 MaxHighOnes =
1173 std::max(Known.countMinLeadingOnes(), Known2.countMinLeadingOnes());
1174 } else if (SPF == SPF_UMIN) {
1175 // We can derive an upper bound on the result by taking the max of the
1176 // leading zero bits.
1177 MaxHighZeros =
1178 std::max(Known.countMinLeadingZeros(), Known2.countMinLeadingZeros());
1179 } else if (SPF == SPF_ABS) {
1180 // RHS from matchSelectPattern returns the negation part of abs pattern.
1181 // If the negate has an NSW flag we can assume the sign bit of the result
1182 // will be 0 because that makes abs(INT_MIN) undefined.
1183 if (Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(cast<Instruction>(RHS)))
1184 MaxHighZeros = 1;
1185 }
1186
1187 // Only known if known in both the LHS and RHS.
1188 Known.One &= Known2.One;
1189 Known.Zero &= Known2.Zero;
1190 if (MaxHighOnes > 0)
1191 Known.One.setHighBits(MaxHighOnes);
1192 if (MaxHighZeros > 0)
1193 Known.Zero.setHighBits(MaxHighZeros);
1194 break;
1195 }
1196 case Instruction::FPTrunc:
1197 case Instruction::FPExt:
1198 case Instruction::FPToUI:
1199 case Instruction::FPToSI:
1200 case Instruction::SIToFP:
1201 case Instruction::UIToFP:
1202 break; // Can't work with floating point.
1203 case Instruction::PtrToInt:
1204 case Instruction::IntToPtr:
1205 // Fall through and handle them the same as zext/trunc.
1206 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
1207 case Instruction::ZExt:
1208 case Instruction::Trunc: {
1209 Type *SrcTy = I->getOperand(0)->getType();
1210
1211 unsigned SrcBitWidth;
1212 // Note that we handle pointer operands here because of inttoptr/ptrtoint
1213 // which fall through here.
1214 Type *ScalarTy = SrcTy->getScalarType();
1215 SrcBitWidth = ScalarTy->isPointerTy() ?
1216 Q.DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy) :
1217 Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy);
1218
1219 assert(SrcBitWidth && "SrcBitWidth can't be zero");
1220 Known = Known.zextOrTrunc(SrcBitWidth, false);
1221 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1222 Known = Known.zextOrTrunc(BitWidth, true /* ExtendedBitsAreKnownZero */);
1223 break;
1224 }
1225 case Instruction::BitCast: {
1226 Type *SrcTy = I->getOperand(0)->getType();
1227 if (SrcTy->isIntOrPtrTy() &&
1228 // TODO: For now, not handling conversions like:
1229 // (bitcast i64 %x to <2 x i32>)
1230 !I->getType()->isVectorTy()) {
1231 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1232 break;
1233 }
1234 break;
1235 }
1236 case Instruction::AddrSpaceCast: {
1237 Type *SrcTy = I->getOperand(0)->getType();
1238 Type *DestTy = I->getType();
1239 // Address space conversions between CHERI capability and integer pointer
1240 // do not affect the virtual address bits
1241 if (SrcTy->isIntOrPtrTy() && isCheriPointer(SrcTy, &Q.DL) != isCheriPointer(DestTy, &Q.DL)) {
1242 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1243 break;
1244 }
1245 break;
1246 }
1247 case Instruction::SExt: {
1248 // Compute the bits in the result that are not present in the input.
1249 unsigned SrcBitWidth = I->getOperand(0)->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
1250
1251 Known = Known.trunc(SrcBitWidth);
1252 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1253 // If the sign bit of the input is known set or clear, then we know the
1254 // top bits of the result.
1255 Known = Known.sext(BitWidth);
1256 break;
1257 }
1258 case Instruction::Shl: {
1259 // (shl X, C1) & C2 == 0 iff (X & C2 >>u C1) == 0
1260 bool NSW = Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(I));
1261 auto KZF = [NSW](const APInt &KnownZero, unsigned ShiftAmt) {
1262 APInt KZResult = KnownZero << ShiftAmt;
1263 KZResult.setLowBits(ShiftAmt); // Low bits known 0.
1264 // If this shift has "nsw" keyword, then the result is either a poison
1265 // value or has the same sign bit as the first operand.
1266 if (NSW && KnownZero.isSignBitSet())
1267 KZResult.setSignBit();
1268 return KZResult;
1269 };
1270
1271 auto KOF = [NSW](const APInt &KnownOne, unsigned ShiftAmt) {
1272 APInt KOResult = KnownOne << ShiftAmt;
1273 if (NSW && KnownOne.isSignBitSet())
1274 KOResult.setSignBit();
1275 return KOResult;
1276 };
1277
1278 computeKnownBitsFromShiftOperator(I, Known, Known2, Depth, Q, KZF, KOF);
1279 break;
1280 }
1281 case Instruction::LShr: {
1282 // (lshr X, C1) & C2 == 0 iff (-1 >> C1) & C2 == 0
1283 auto KZF = [](const APInt &KnownZero, unsigned ShiftAmt) {
1284 APInt KZResult = KnownZero.lshr(ShiftAmt);
1285 // High bits known zero.
1286 KZResult.setHighBits(ShiftAmt);
1287 return KZResult;
1288 };
1289
1290 auto KOF = [](const APInt &KnownOne, unsigned ShiftAmt) {
1291 return KnownOne.lshr(ShiftAmt);
1292 };
1293
1294 computeKnownBitsFromShiftOperator(I, Known, Known2, Depth, Q, KZF, KOF);
1295 break;
1296 }
1297 case Instruction::AShr: {
1298 // (ashr X, C1) & C2 == 0 iff (-1 >> C1) & C2 == 0
1299 auto KZF = [](const APInt &KnownZero, unsigned ShiftAmt) {
1300 return KnownZero.ashr(ShiftAmt);
1301 };
1302
1303 auto KOF = [](const APInt &KnownOne, unsigned ShiftAmt) {
1304 return KnownOne.ashr(ShiftAmt);
1305 };
1306
1307 computeKnownBitsFromShiftOperator(I, Known, Known2, Depth, Q, KZF, KOF);
1308 break;
1309 }
1310 case Instruction::Sub: {
1311 bool NSW = Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(I));
1312 computeKnownBitsAddSub(false, I->getOperand(0), I->getOperand(1), NSW,
1313 Known, Known2, Depth, Q);
1314 break;
1315 }
1316 case Instruction::Add: {
1317 bool NSW = Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(I));
1318 computeKnownBitsAddSub(true, I->getOperand(0), I->getOperand(1), NSW,
1319 Known, Known2, Depth, Q);
1320 break;
1321 }
1322 case Instruction::SRem:
1323 if (ConstantInt *Rem = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1))) {
1324 APInt RA = Rem->getValue().abs();
1325 if (RA.isPowerOf2()) {
1326 APInt LowBits = RA - 1;
1327 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1328
1329 // The low bits of the first operand are unchanged by the srem.
1330 Known.Zero = Known2.Zero & LowBits;
1331 Known.One = Known2.One & LowBits;
1332
1333 // If the first operand is non-negative or has all low bits zero, then
1334 // the upper bits are all zero.
1335 if (Known2.isNonNegative() || LowBits.isSubsetOf(Known2.Zero))
1336 Known.Zero |= ~LowBits;
1337
1338 // If the first operand is negative and not all low bits are zero, then
1339 // the upper bits are all one.
1340 if (Known2.isNegative() && LowBits.intersects(Known2.One))
1341 Known.One |= ~LowBits;
1342
1343 assert((Known.Zero & Known.One) == 0 && "Bits known to be one AND zero?");
1344 break;
1345 }
1346 }
1347
1348 // The sign bit is the LHS's sign bit, except when the result of the
1349 // remainder is zero.
1350 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1351 // If it's known zero, our sign bit is also zero.
1352 if (Known2.isNonNegative())
1353 Known.makeNonNegative();
1354
1355 break;
1356 case Instruction::URem: {
1357 if (ConstantInt *Rem = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1))) {
1358 const APInt &RA = Rem->getValue();
1359 if (RA.isPowerOf2()) {
1360 APInt LowBits = (RA - 1);
1361 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1362 Known.Zero |= ~LowBits;
1363 Known.One &= LowBits;
1364 break;
1365 }
1366 }
1367
1368 // Since the result is less than or equal to either operand, any leading
1369 // zero bits in either operand must also exist in the result.
1370 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1371 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1372
1373 unsigned Leaders =
1374 std::max(Known.countMinLeadingZeros(), Known2.countMinLeadingZeros());
1375 Known.resetAll();
1376 Known.Zero.setHighBits(Leaders);
1377 break;
1378 }
1379
1380 case Instruction::Alloca: {
1381 const AllocaInst *AI = cast<AllocaInst>(I);
1382 unsigned Align = AI->getAlignment();
1383 if (Align == 0)
1384 Align = Q.DL.getABITypeAlignment(AI->getAllocatedType());
1385
1386 if (Align > 0)
1387 Known.Zero.setLowBits(countTrailingZeros(Align));
1388 break;
1389 }
1390 case Instruction::GetElementPtr: {
1391 // Analyze all of the subscripts of this getelementptr instruction
1392 // to determine if we can prove known low zero bits.
1393 KnownBits LocalKnown(BitWidth);
1394 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), LocalKnown, Depth + 1, Q);
1395 unsigned TrailZ = LocalKnown.countMinTrailingZeros();
1396
1397 gep_type_iterator GTI = gep_type_begin(I);
1398 for (unsigned i = 1, e = I->getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i, ++GTI) {
1399 Value *Index = I->getOperand(i);
1400 if (StructType *STy = GTI.getStructTypeOrNull()) {
1401 // Handle struct member offset arithmetic.
1402
1403 // Handle case when index is vector zeroinitializer
1404 Constant *CIndex = cast<Constant>(Index);
1405 if (CIndex->isZeroValue())
1406 continue;
1407
1408 if (CIndex->getType()->isVectorTy())
1409 Index = CIndex->getSplatValue();
1410
1411 unsigned Idx = cast<ConstantInt>(Index)->getZExtValue();
1412 const StructLayout *SL = Q.DL.getStructLayout(STy);
1413 uint64_t Offset = SL->getElementOffset(Idx);
1414 TrailZ = std::min<unsigned>(TrailZ,
1415 countTrailingZeros(Offset));
1416 } else {
1417 // Handle array index arithmetic.
1418 Type *IndexedTy = GTI.getIndexedType();
1419 if (!IndexedTy->isSized()) {
1420 TrailZ = 0;
1421 break;
1422 }
1423 unsigned GEPOpiBits = Index->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
1424 uint64_t TypeSize = Q.DL.getTypeAllocSize(IndexedTy);
1425 LocalKnown.Zero = LocalKnown.One = APInt(GEPOpiBits, 0);
1426 computeKnownBits(Index, LocalKnown, Depth + 1, Q);
1427 TrailZ = std::min(TrailZ,
1428 unsigned(countTrailingZeros(TypeSize) +
1429 LocalKnown.countMinTrailingZeros()));
1430 }
1431 }
1432
1433 Known.Zero.setLowBits(TrailZ);
1434 break;
1435 }
1436 case Instruction::PHI: {
1437 const PHINode *P = cast<PHINode>(I);
1438 // Handle the case of a simple two-predecessor recurrence PHI.
1439 // There's a lot more that could theoretically be done here, but
1440 // this is sufficient to catch some interesting cases.
1441 if (P->getNumIncomingValues() == 2) {
1442 for (unsigned i = 0; i != 2; ++i) {
1443 Value *L = P->getIncomingValue(i);
1444 Value *R = P->getIncomingValue(!i);
1445 Operator *LU = dyn_cast<Operator>(L);
1446 if (!LU)
1447 continue;
1448 unsigned Opcode = LU->getOpcode();
1449 // Check for operations that have the property that if
1450 // both their operands have low zero bits, the result
1451 // will have low zero bits.
1452 if (Opcode == Instruction::Add ||
1453 Opcode == Instruction::Sub ||
1454 Opcode == Instruction::And ||
1455 Opcode == Instruction::Or ||
1456 Opcode == Instruction::Mul) {
1457 Value *LL = LU->getOperand(0);
1458 Value *LR = LU->getOperand(1);
1459 // Find a recurrence.
1460 if (LL == I)
1461 L = LR;
1462 else if (LR == I)
1463 L = LL;
1464 else
1465 break;
1466 // Ok, we have a PHI of the form L op= R. Check for low
1467 // zero bits.
1468 computeKnownBits(R, Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1469
1470 // We need to take the minimum number of known bits
1471 KnownBits Known3(Known);
1472 computeKnownBits(L, Known3, Depth + 1, Q);
1473
1474 Known.Zero.setLowBits(std::min(Known2.countMinTrailingZeros(),
1475 Known3.countMinTrailingZeros()));
1476
1477 auto *OverflowOp = dyn_cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(LU);
1478 if (OverflowOp && Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(OverflowOp)) {
1479 // If initial value of recurrence is nonnegative, and we are adding
1480 // a nonnegative number with nsw, the result can only be nonnegative
1481 // or poison value regardless of the number of times we execute the
1482 // add in phi recurrence. If initial value is negative and we are
1483 // adding a negative number with nsw, the result can only be
1484 // negative or poison value. Similar arguments apply to sub and mul.
1485 //
1486 // (add non-negative, non-negative) --> non-negative
1487 // (add negative, negative) --> negative
1488 if (Opcode == Instruction::Add) {
1489 if (Known2.isNonNegative() && Known3.isNonNegative())
1490 Known.makeNonNegative();
1491 else if (Known2.isNegative() && Known3.isNegative())
1492 Known.makeNegative();
1493 }
1494
1495 // (sub nsw non-negative, negative) --> non-negative
1496 // (sub nsw negative, non-negative) --> negative
1497 else if (Opcode == Instruction::Sub && LL == I) {
1498 if (Known2.isNonNegative() && Known3.isNegative())
1499 Known.makeNonNegative();
1500 else if (Known2.isNegative() && Known3.isNonNegative())
1501 Known.makeNegative();
1502 }
1503
1504 // (mul nsw non-negative, non-negative) --> non-negative
1505 else if (Opcode == Instruction::Mul && Known2.isNonNegative() &&
1506 Known3.isNonNegative())
1507 Known.makeNonNegative();
1508 }
1509
1510 break;
1511 }
1512 }
1513 }
1514
1515 // Unreachable blocks may have zero-operand PHI nodes.
1516 if (P->getNumIncomingValues() == 0)
1517 break;
1518
1519 // Otherwise take the unions of the known bit sets of the operands,
1520 // taking conservative care to avoid excessive recursion.
1521 if (Depth < MaxDepth - 1 && !Known.Zero && !Known.One) {
1522 // Skip if every incoming value references to ourself.
1523 if (dyn_cast_or_null<UndefValue>(P->hasConstantValue()))
1524 break;
1525
1526 Known.Zero.setAllBits();
1527 Known.One.setAllBits();
1528 for (Value *IncValue : P->incoming_values()) {
1529 // Skip direct self references.
1530 if (IncValue == P) continue;
1531
1532 Known2 = KnownBits(BitWidth);
1533 // Recurse, but cap the recursion to one level, because we don't
1534 // want to waste time spinning around in loops.
1535 computeKnownBits(IncValue, Known2, MaxDepth - 1, Q);
1536 Known.Zero &= Known2.Zero;
1537 Known.One &= Known2.One;
1538 // If all bits have been ruled out, there's no need to check
1539 // more operands.
1540 if (!Known.Zero && !Known.One)
1541 break;
1542 }
1543 }
1544 break;
1545 }
1546 case Instruction::Call:
1547 case Instruction::Invoke:
1548 // If range metadata is attached to this call, set known bits from that,
1549 // and then intersect with known bits based on other properties of the
1550 // function.
1551 if (MDNode *MD =
1552 Q.IIQ.getMetadata(cast<Instruction>(I), LLVMContext::MD_range))
1553 computeKnownBitsFromRangeMetadata(*MD, Known);
1554 if (const Value *RV = ImmutableCallSite(I).getReturnedArgOperand()) {
1555 computeKnownBits(RV, Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1556 Known.Zero |= Known2.Zero;
1557 Known.One |= Known2.One;
1558 }
1559 if (const IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(I)) {
1560 switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
1561 default: break;
1562 case Intrinsic::bitreverse:
1563 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1564 Known.Zero |= Known2.Zero.reverseBits();
1565 Known.One |= Known2.One.reverseBits();
1566 break;
1567 case Intrinsic::bswap:
1568 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1569 Known.Zero |= Known2.Zero.byteSwap();
1570 Known.One |= Known2.One.byteSwap();
1571 break;
1572 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_address_get: {
1573 // This just fetches the virtual address -> treat the same as ptrtoint:
1574 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1575 break;
1576 }
1577 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_address_set: {
1578 // We can treat it the same as inttoptr:
1579 // The virtual address after csetaddr will be the second argument.
1580 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1581 break;
1582 }
1583 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_offset_increment: {
1584 bool NSW = false;
1585 computeKnownBitsAddSub(true, I->getOperand(0), I->getOperand(1), NSW,
1586 Known, Known2, Depth, Q);
1587 break;
1588 }
1589 case Intrinsic::cheri_cap_diff: {
1590 bool NSW = false;
1591 computeKnownBitsAddSub(false, I->getOperand(0), I->getOperand(1), NSW,
1592 Known, Known2, Depth, Q);
1593 break;
1594 }
1595 case Intrinsic::ctlz: {
1596 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1597 // If we have a known 1, its position is our upper bound.
1598 unsigned PossibleLZ = Known2.One.countLeadingZeros();
1599 // If this call is undefined for 0, the result will be less than 2^n.
1600 if (II->getArgOperand(1) == ConstantInt::getTrue(II->getContext()))
1601 PossibleLZ = std::min(PossibleLZ, BitWidth - 1);
1602 unsigned LowBits = Log2_32(PossibleLZ)+1;
1603 Known.Zero.setBitsFrom(LowBits);
1604 break;
1605 }
1606 case Intrinsic::cttz: {
1607 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1608 // If we have a known 1, its position is our upper bound.
1609 unsigned PossibleTZ = Known2.One.countTrailingZeros();
1610 // If this call is undefined for 0, the result will be less than 2^n.
1611 if (II->getArgOperand(1) == ConstantInt::getTrue(II->getContext()))
1612 PossibleTZ = std::min(PossibleTZ, BitWidth - 1);
1613 unsigned LowBits = Log2_32(PossibleTZ)+1;
1614 Known.Zero.setBitsFrom(LowBits);
1615 break;
1616 }
1617 case Intrinsic::ctpop: {
1618 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1619 // We can bound the space the count needs. Also, bits known to be zero
1620 // can't contribute to the population.
1621 unsigned BitsPossiblySet = Known2.countMaxPopulation();
1622 unsigned LowBits = Log2_32(BitsPossiblySet)+1;
1623 Known.Zero.setBitsFrom(LowBits);
1624 // TODO: we could bound KnownOne using the lower bound on the number
1625 // of bits which might be set provided by popcnt KnownOne2.
1626 break;
1627 }
1628 case Intrinsic::fshr:
1629 case Intrinsic::fshl: {
1630 const APInt *SA;
1631 if (!match(I->getOperand(2), m_APInt(SA)))
1632 break;
1633
1634 // Normalize to funnel shift left.
1635 uint64_t ShiftAmt = SA->urem(BitWidth);
1636 if (II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::fshr)
1637 ShiftAmt = BitWidth - ShiftAmt;
1638
1639 KnownBits Known3(Known);
1640 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1641 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known3, Depth + 1, Q);
1642
1643 Known.Zero =
1644 Known2.Zero.shl(ShiftAmt) | Known3.Zero.lshr(BitWidth - ShiftAmt);
1645 Known.One =
1646 Known2.One.shl(ShiftAmt) | Known3.One.lshr(BitWidth - ShiftAmt);
1647 break;
1648 }
1649 case Intrinsic::uadd_sat:
1650 case Intrinsic::usub_sat: {
1651 bool IsAdd = II->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::uadd_sat;
1652 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1653 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(1), Known2, Depth + 1, Q);
1654
1655 // Add: Leading ones of either operand are preserved.
1656 // Sub: Leading zeros of LHS and leading ones of RHS are preserved
1657 // as leading zeros in the result.
1658 unsigned LeadingKnown;
1659 if (IsAdd)
1660 LeadingKnown = std::max(Known.countMinLeadingOnes(),
1661 Known2.countMinLeadingOnes());
1662 else
1663 LeadingKnown = std::max(Known.countMinLeadingZeros(),
1664 Known2.countMinLeadingOnes());
1665
1666 Known = KnownBits::computeForAddSub(
1667 IsAdd, /* NSW */ false, Known, Known2);
1668
1669 // We select between the operation result and all-ones/zero
1670 // respectively, so we can preserve known ones/zeros.
1671 if (IsAdd) {
1672 Known.One.setHighBits(LeadingKnown);
1673 Known.Zero.clearAllBits();
1674 } else {
1675 Known.Zero.setHighBits(LeadingKnown);
1676 Known.One.clearAllBits();
1677 }
1678 break;
1679 }
1680 case Intrinsic::x86_sse42_crc32_64_64:
1681 Known.Zero.setBitsFrom(32);
1682 break;
1683 }
1684 }
1685 break;
1686 case Instruction::ExtractElement:
1687 // Look through extract element. At the moment we keep this simple and skip
1688 // tracking the specific element. But at least we might find information
1689 // valid for all elements of the vector (for example if vector is sign
1690 // extended, shifted, etc).
1691 computeKnownBits(I->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1692 break;
1693 case Instruction::ExtractValue:
1694 if (IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(I->getOperand(0))) {
1695 const ExtractValueInst *EVI = cast<ExtractValueInst>(I);
1696 if (EVI->getNumIndices() != 1) break;
1697 if (EVI->getIndices()[0] == 0) {
1698 switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
1699 default: break;
1700 case Intrinsic::uadd_with_overflow:
1701 case Intrinsic::sadd_with_overflow:
1702 computeKnownBitsAddSub(true, II->getArgOperand(0),
1703 II->getArgOperand(1), false, Known, Known2,
1704 Depth, Q);
1705 break;
1706 case Intrinsic::usub_with_overflow:
1707 case Intrinsic::ssub_with_overflow:
1708 computeKnownBitsAddSub(false, II->getArgOperand(0),
1709 II->getArgOperand(1), false, Known, Known2,
1710 Depth, Q);
1711 break;
1712 case Intrinsic::umul_with_overflow:
1713 case Intrinsic::smul_with_overflow:
1714 computeKnownBitsMul(II->getArgOperand(0), II->getArgOperand(1), false,
1715 Known, Known2, Depth, Q);
1716 break;
1717 }
1718 }
1719 }
1720 }
1721}
1722
1723/// Determine which bits of V are known to be either zero or one and return
1724/// them.
1725KnownBits computeKnownBits(const Value *V, unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
1726 KnownBits Known(getBitWidth(V->getType(), Q.DL));
1727 computeKnownBits(V, Known, Depth, Q);
1728 return Known;
1729}
1730
1731/// Determine which bits of V are known to be either zero or one and return
1732/// them in the Known bit set.
1733///
1734/// NOTE: we cannot consider 'undef' to be "IsZero" here. The problem is that
1735/// we cannot optimize based on the assumption that it is zero without changing
1736/// it to be an explicit zero. If we don't change it to zero, other code could
1737/// optimized based on the contradictory assumption that it is non-zero.
1738/// Because instcombine aggressively folds operations with undef args anyway,
1739/// this won't lose us code quality.
1740///
1741/// This function is defined on values with integer type, values with pointer
1742/// type, and vectors of integers. In the case
1743/// where V is a vector, known zero, and known one values are the
1744/// same width as the vector element, and the bit is set only if it is true
1745/// for all of the elements in the vector.
1746void computeKnownBits(const Value *V, KnownBits &Known, unsigned Depth,
1747 const Query &Q) {
1748 assert(V && "No Value?");
1749 assert(Depth <= MaxDepth && "Limit Search Depth");
1750 unsigned BitWidth = Known.getBitWidth();
1751
1752 assert((V->getType()->isIntOrIntVectorTy(BitWidth) ||
1753 V->getType()->isPtrOrPtrVectorTy()) &&
1754 "Not integer or pointer type!");
1755
1756 Type *ScalarTy = V->getType()->getScalarType();
1757 unsigned ExpectedWidth = ScalarTy->isPointerTy() ?
1758 Q.DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy) : Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy);
1759 assert(ExpectedWidth == BitWidth && "V and Known should have same BitWidth");
1760 (void)BitWidth;
1761 (void)ExpectedWidth;
1762
1763 const APInt *C;
1764 if (match(V, m_APInt(C))) {
1765 // We know all of the bits for a scalar constant or a splat vector constant!
1766 Known.One = *C;
1767 Known.Zero = ~Known.One;
1768 return;
1769 }
1770 // Null and aggregate-zero are all-zeros.
1771 if (isa<ConstantPointerNull>(V) || isa<ConstantAggregateZero>(V)) {
1772 Known.setAllZero();
1773 return;
1774 }
1775 // Handle a constant vector by taking the intersection of the known bits of
1776 // each element.
1777 if (const ConstantDataSequential *CDS = dyn_cast<ConstantDataSequential>(V)) {
1778 // We know that CDS must be a vector of integers. Take the intersection of
1779 // each element.
1780 Known.Zero.setAllBits(); Known.One.setAllBits();
1781 for (unsigned i = 0, e = CDS->getNumElements(); i != e; ++i) {
1782 APInt Elt = CDS->getElementAsAPInt(i);
1783 Known.Zero &= ~Elt;
1784 Known.One &= Elt;
1785 }
1786 return;
1787 }
1788
1789 if (const auto *CV = dyn_cast<ConstantVector>(V)) {
1790 // We know that CV must be a vector of integers. Take the intersection of
1791 // each element.
1792 Known.Zero.setAllBits(); Known.One.setAllBits();
1793 for (unsigned i = 0, e = CV->getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) {
1794 Constant *Element = CV->getAggregateElement(i);
1795 auto *ElementCI = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(Element);
1796 if (!ElementCI) {
1797 Known.resetAll();
1798 return;
1799 }
1800 const APInt &Elt = ElementCI->getValue();
1801 Known.Zero &= ~Elt;
1802 Known.One &= Elt;
1803 }
1804 return;
1805 }
1806
1807 // Start out not knowing anything.
1808 Known.resetAll();
1809
1810 // We can't imply anything about undefs.
1811 if (isa<UndefValue>(V))
1812 return;
1813
1814 // There's no point in looking through other users of ConstantData for
1815 // assumptions. Confirm that we've handled them all.
1816 assert(!isa<ConstantData>(V) && "Unhandled constant data!");
1817
1818 // Limit search depth.
1819 // All recursive calls that increase depth must come after this.
1820 if (Depth == MaxDepth)
1821 return;
1822
1823 // A weak GlobalAlias is totally unknown. A non-weak GlobalAlias has
1824 // the bits of its aliasee.
1825 if (const GlobalAlias *GA = dyn_cast<GlobalAlias>(V)) {
1826 if (!GA->isInterposable())
1827 computeKnownBits(GA->getAliasee(), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
1828 return;
1829 }
1830
1831 if (const Operator *I = dyn_cast<Operator>(V))
1832 computeKnownBitsFromOperator(I, Known, Depth, Q);
1833
1834 // Aligned pointers have trailing zeros - refine Known.Zero set
1835 if (V->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
1836 unsigned Align = V->getPointerAlignment(Q.DL);
1837 if (Align)
1838 Known.Zero.setLowBits(countTrailingZeros(Align));
1839 }
1840
1841 // computeKnownBitsFromAssume strictly refines Known.
1842 // Therefore, we run them after computeKnownBitsFromOperator.
1843
1844 // Check whether a nearby assume intrinsic can determine some known bits.
1845 computeKnownBitsFromAssume(V, Known, Depth, Q);
1846
1847 assert((Known.Zero & Known.One) == 0 && "Bits known to be one AND zero?");
1848}
1849
1850/// Return true if the given value is known to have exactly one
1851/// bit set when defined. For vectors return true if every element is known to
1852/// be a power of two when defined. Supports values with integer or pointer
1853/// types and vectors of integers.
1854bool isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(const Value *V, bool OrZero, unsigned Depth,
1855 const Query &Q) {
1856 assert(Depth <= MaxDepth && "Limit Search Depth");
1857
1858 // Attempt to match against constants.
1859 if (OrZero && match(V, m_Power2OrZero()))
1860 return true;
1861 if (match(V, m_Power2()))
1862 return true;
1863
1864 // 1 << X is clearly a power of two if the one is not shifted off the end. If
1865 // it is shifted off the end then the result is undefined.
1866 if (match(V, m_Shl(m_One(), m_Value())))
1867 return true;
1868
1869 // (signmask) >>l X is clearly a power of two if the one is not shifted off
1870 // the bottom. If it is shifted off the bottom then the result is undefined.
1871 if (match(V, m_LShr(m_SignMask(), m_Value())))
1872 return true;
1873
1874 // The remaining tests are all recursive, so bail out if we hit the limit.
1875 if (Depth++ == MaxDepth)
1876 return false;
1877
1878 Value *X = nullptr, *Y = nullptr;
1879 // A shift left or a logical shift right of a power of two is a power of two
1880 // or zero.
1881 if (OrZero && (match(V, m_Shl(m_Value(X), m_Value())) ||
1882 match(V, m_LShr(m_Value(X), m_Value()))))
1883 return isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(X, /*OrZero*/ true, Depth, Q);
1884
1885 if (const ZExtInst *ZI = dyn_cast<ZExtInst>(V))
1886 return isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(ZI->getOperand(0), OrZero, Depth, Q);
1887
1888 if (const SelectInst *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V))
1889 return isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(SI->getTrueValue(), OrZero, Depth, Q) &&
1890 isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(SI->getFalseValue(), OrZero, Depth, Q);
1891
1892 if (OrZero && match(V, m_And(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) {
1893 // A power of two and'd with anything is a power of two or zero.
1894 if (isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(X, /*OrZero*/ true, Depth, Q) ||
1895 isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(Y, /*OrZero*/ true, Depth, Q))
1896 return true;
1897 // X & (-X) is always a power of two or zero.
1898 if (match(X, m_Neg(m_Specific(Y))) || match(Y, m_Neg(m_Specific(X))))
1899 return true;
1900 return false;
1901 }
1902
1903 // Adding a power-of-two or zero to the same power-of-two or zero yields
1904 // either the original power-of-two, a larger power-of-two or zero.
1905 if (match(V, m_Add(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) {
1906 const OverflowingBinaryOperator *VOBO = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V);
1907 if (OrZero || Q.IIQ.hasNoUnsignedWrap(VOBO) ||
1908 Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(VOBO)) {
1909 if (match(X, m_And(m_Specific(Y), m_Value())) ||
1910 match(X, m_And(m_Value(), m_Specific(Y))))
1911 if (isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(Y, OrZero, Depth, Q))
1912 return true;
1913 if (match(Y, m_And(m_Specific(X), m_Value())) ||
1914 match(Y, m_And(m_Value(), m_Specific(X))))
1915 if (isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(X, OrZero, Depth, Q))
1916 return true;
1917
1918 unsigned BitWidth = V->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
1919 KnownBits LHSBits(BitWidth);
1920 computeKnownBits(X, LHSBits, Depth, Q);
1921
1922 KnownBits RHSBits(BitWidth);
1923 computeKnownBits(Y, RHSBits, Depth, Q);
1924 // If i8 V is a power of two or zero:
1925 // ZeroBits: 1 1 1 0 1 1 1 1
1926 // ~ZeroBits: 0 0 0 1 0 0 0 0
1927 if ((~(LHSBits.Zero & RHSBits.Zero)).isPowerOf2())
1928 // If OrZero isn't set, we cannot give back a zero result.
1929 // Make sure either the LHS or RHS has a bit set.
1930 if (OrZero || RHSBits.One.getBoolValue() || LHSBits.One.getBoolValue())
1931 return true;
1932 }
1933 }
1934
1935 // An exact divide or right shift can only shift off zero bits, so the result
1936 // is a power of two only if the first operand is a power of two and not
1937 // copying a sign bit (sdiv int_min, 2).
1938 if (match(V, m_Exact(m_LShr(m_Value(), m_Value()))) ||
1939 match(V, m_Exact(m_UDiv(m_Value(), m_Value())))) {
1940 return isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(cast<Operator>(V)->getOperand(0), OrZero,
1941 Depth, Q);
1942 }
1943
1944 return false;
1945}
1946
1947/// Test whether a GEP's result is known to be non-null.
1948///
1949/// Uses properties inherent in a GEP to try to determine whether it is known
1950/// to be non-null.
1951///
1952/// Currently this routine does not support vector GEPs.
1953static bool isGEPKnownNonNull(const GEPOperator *GEP, unsigned Depth,
1954 const Query &Q) {
1955 const Function *F = nullptr;
1956 if (const Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(GEP))
1957 F = I->getFunction();
1958
1959 if (!GEP->isInBounds() ||
1960 NullPointerIsDefined(F, GEP->getPointerAddressSpace()))
1961 return false;
1962
1963 // FIXME: Support vector-GEPs.
1964 assert(GEP->getType()->isPointerTy() && "We only support plain pointer GEP");
1965
1966 // If the base pointer is non-null, we cannot walk to a null address with an
1967 // inbounds GEP in address space zero.
1968 if (isKnownNonZero(GEP->getPointerOperand(), Depth, Q))
1969 return true;
1970
1971 // Walk the GEP operands and see if any operand introduces a non-zero offset.
1972 // If so, then the GEP cannot produce a null pointer, as doing so would
1973 // inherently violate the inbounds contract within address space zero.
1974 for (gep_type_iterator GTI = gep_type_begin(GEP), GTE = gep_type_end(GEP);
1975 GTI != GTE; ++GTI) {
1976 // Struct types are easy -- they must always be indexed by a constant.
1977 if (StructType *STy = GTI.getStructTypeOrNull()) {
1978 ConstantInt *OpC = cast<ConstantInt>(GTI.getOperand());
1979 unsigned ElementIdx = OpC->getZExtValue();
1980 const StructLayout *SL = Q.DL.getStructLayout(STy);
1981 uint64_t ElementOffset = SL->getElementOffset(ElementIdx);
1982 if (ElementOffset > 0)
1983 return true;
1984 continue;
1985 }
1986
1987 // If we have a zero-sized type, the index doesn't matter. Keep looping.
1988 if (Q.DL.getTypeAllocSize(GTI.getIndexedType()) == 0)
1989 continue;
1990
1991 // Fast path the constant operand case both for efficiency and so we don't
1992 // increment Depth when just zipping down an all-constant GEP.
1993 if (ConstantInt *OpC = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(GTI.getOperand())) {
1994 if (!OpC->isZero())
1995 return true;
1996 continue;
1997 }
1998
1999 // We post-increment Depth here because while isKnownNonZero increments it
2000 // as well, when we pop back up that increment won't persist. We don't want
2001 // to recurse 10k times just because we have 10k GEP operands. We don't
2002 // bail completely out because we want to handle constant GEPs regardless
2003 // of depth.
2004 if (Depth++ >= MaxDepth)
2005 continue;
2006
2007 if (isKnownNonZero(GTI.getOperand(), Depth, Q))
2008 return true;
2009 }
2010
2011 return false;
2012}
2013
2014static bool isKnownNonNullFromDominatingCondition(const Value *V,
2015 const Instruction *CtxI,
2016 const DominatorTree *DT) {
2017 assert(V->getType()->isPointerTy() && "V must be pointer type");
2018 assert(!isa<ConstantData>(V) && "Did not expect ConstantPointerNull");
2019
2020 if (!CtxI || !DT)
2021 return false;
2022
2023 unsigned NumUsesExplored = 0;
2024 for (auto *U : V->users()) {
2025 // Avoid massive lists
2026 if (NumUsesExplored >= DomConditionsMaxUses)
2027 break;
2028 NumUsesExplored++;
2029
2030 // If the value is used as an argument to a call or invoke, then argument
2031 // attributes may provide an answer about null-ness.
2032 if (auto CS = ImmutableCallSite(U))
2033 if (auto *CalledFunc = CS.getCalledFunction())
2034 for (const Argument &Arg : CalledFunc->args())
2035 if (CS.getArgOperand(Arg.getArgNo()) == V &&
2036 Arg.hasNonNullAttr() && DT->dominates(CS.getInstruction(), CtxI))
2037 return true;
2038
2039 // Consider only compare instructions uniquely controlling a branch
2040 CmpInst::Predicate Pred;
2041 if (!match(const_cast<User *>(U),
2042 m_c_ICmp(Pred, m_Specific(V), m_Zero())) ||
2043 (Pred != ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ && Pred != ICmpInst::ICMP_NE))
2044 continue;
2045
2046 SmallVector<const User *, 4> WorkList;
2047 SmallPtrSet<const User *, 4> Visited;
2048 for (auto *CmpU : U->users()) {
2049 assert(WorkList.empty() && "Should be!");
2050 if (Visited.insert(CmpU).second)
2051 WorkList.push_back(CmpU);
2052
2053 while (!WorkList.empty()) {
2054 auto *Curr = WorkList.pop_back_val();
2055
2056 // If a user is an AND, add all its users to the work list. We only
2057 // propagate "pred != null" condition through AND because it is only
2058 // correct to assume that all conditions of AND are met in true branch.
2059 // TODO: Support similar logic of OR and EQ predicate?
2060 if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE)
2061 if (auto *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(Curr))
2062 if (BO->getOpcode() == Instruction::And) {
2063 for (auto *BOU : BO->users())
2064 if (Visited.insert(BOU).second)
2065 WorkList.push_back(BOU);
2066 continue;
2067 }
2068
2069 if (const BranchInst *BI = dyn_cast<BranchInst>(Curr)) {
2070 assert(BI->isConditional() && "uses a comparison!");
2071
2072 BasicBlock *NonNullSuccessor =
2073 BI->getSuccessor(Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ ? 1 : 0);
2074 BasicBlockEdge Edge(BI->getParent(), NonNullSuccessor);
2075 if (Edge.isSingleEdge() && DT->dominates(Edge, CtxI->getParent()))
2076 return true;
2077 } else if (Pred == ICmpInst::ICMP_NE && isGuard(Curr) &&
2078 DT->dominates(cast<Instruction>(Curr), CtxI)) {
2079 return true;
2080 }
2081 }
2082 }
2083 }
2084
2085 return false;
2086}
