2088/// Does the 'Range' metadata (which must be a valid MD_range operand list)
2089/// ensure that the value it's attached to is never Value? 'RangeType' is
2090/// is the type of the value described by the range.
2091static bool rangeMetadataExcludesValue(const MDNode* Ranges, const APInt& Value) {
2092 const unsigned NumRanges = Ranges->getNumOperands() / 2;
2093 assert(NumRanges >= 1);
2094 for (unsigned i = 0; i < NumRanges; ++i) {
2095 ConstantInt *Lower =
2096 mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(Ranges->getOperand(2 * i + 0));
2097 ConstantInt *Upper =
2098 mdconst::extract<ConstantInt>(Ranges->getOperand(2 * i + 1));
2099 ConstantRange Range(Lower->getValue(), Upper->getValue());
2100 if (Range.contains(Value))
2101 return false;
2102 }
2103 return true;
2104}
2105
2106/// Return true if the given value is known to be non-zero when defined. For
2107/// vectors, return true if every element is known to be non-zero when
2108/// defined. For pointers, if the context instruction and dominator tree are
2109/// specified, perform context-sensitive analysis and return true if the
2110/// pointer couldn't possibly be null at the specified instruction.
2111/// Supports values with integer or pointer type and vectors of integers.
2112bool isKnownNonZero(const Value *V, unsigned Depth, const Query &Q) {
2113 if (auto *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
2114 if (C->isNullValue())
2115 return false;
2116 if (isa<ConstantInt>(C))
2117 // Must be non-zero due to null test above.
2118 return true;
2119
2120 // For constant vectors, check that all elements are undefined or known
2121 // non-zero to determine that the whole vector is known non-zero.
2122 if (auto *VecTy = dyn_cast<VectorType>(C->getType())) {
2123 for (unsigned i = 0, e = VecTy->getNumElements(); i != e; ++i) {
2124 Constant *Elt = C->getAggregateElement(i);
2125 if (!Elt || Elt->isNullValue())
2126 return false;
2127 if (!isa<UndefValue>(Elt) && !isa<ConstantInt>(Elt))
2128 return false;
2129 }
2130 return true;
2131 }
2132
2133 // A global variable in address space 0 is non null unless extern weak
2134 // or an absolute symbol reference. Other address spaces may have null as a
2135 // valid address for a global, so we can't assume anything.
2136 if (const GlobalValue *GV = dyn_cast<GlobalValue>(V)) {
2137 if (!GV->isAbsoluteSymbolRef() && !GV->hasExternalWeakLinkage()) {
2138 unsigned GVAddrSpace = GV->getType()->getAddressSpace();
2139 if (GVAddrSpace == 0 || Q.DL.isFatPointer(GVAddrSpace))
2140 return true;
2141 }
2142 } else
2143 return false;
2144 }
2145
2146 if (auto *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
2147 if (MDNode *Ranges = Q.IIQ.getMetadata(I, LLVMContext::MD_range)) {
2148 // If the possible ranges don't contain zero, then the value is
2149 // definitely non-zero.
2150 if (auto *Ty = dyn_cast<IntegerType>(V->getType())) {
2151 const APInt ZeroValue(Ty->getBitWidth(), 0);
2152 if (rangeMetadataExcludesValue(Ranges, ZeroValue))
2153 return true;
2154 }
2155 }
2156 }
2157
2158 // Some of the tests below are recursive, so bail out if we hit the limit.
2159 if (Depth++ >= MaxDepth)
2160 return false;
2161
2162 // Check for pointer simplifications.
2163 if (V->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
2164 // Alloca never returns null, malloc might.
2165 if (isa<AllocaInst>(V)) {
2166 unsigned AS = Q.DL.getAllocaAddrSpace();
2167 // XXXAR: AMDGPU broke this because their allocaAddressSpace is weird
2168 if (AS == 0 || Q.DL.isFatPointer(AS))
2169 return true;
2170 }
2171
2172 // A byval, inalloca, or nonnull argument is never null.
2173 if (const Argument *A = dyn_cast<Argument>(V))
2174 if (A->hasByValOrInAllocaAttr() || A->hasNonNullAttr())
2175 return true;
2176
2177 // A Load tagged with nonnull metadata is never null.
2178 if (const LoadInst *LI = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(V))
2179 if (Q.IIQ.getMetadata(LI, LLVMContext::MD_nonnull))
2180 return true;
2181
2182 if (const auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
2183 if (Call->isReturnNonNull())
2184 return true;
2185 if (const auto *RP = getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer(Call))
2186 return isKnownNonZero(RP, Depth, Q);
2187 }
2188 }
2189
2190
2191 // Check for recursive pointer simplifications.
2192 if (V->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
2193 if (isKnownNonNullFromDominatingCondition(V, Q.CxtI, Q.DT))
2194 return true;
2195
2196 // Look through bitcast operations, GEPs, and int2ptr instructions as they
2197 // do not alter the value, or at least not the nullness property of the
2198 // value, e.g., int2ptr is allowed to zero/sign extend the value.
2199 //
2200 // Note that we have to take special care to avoid looking through
2201 // truncating casts, e.g., int2ptr/ptr2int with appropriate sizes, as well
2202 // as casts that can alter the value, e.g., AddrSpaceCasts.
2203 if (const GEPOperator *GEP = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(V))
2204 if (isGEPKnownNonNull(GEP, Depth, Q))
2205 return true;
2206
2207 if (auto *BCO = dyn_cast<BitCastOperator>(V))
2208 return isKnownNonZero(BCO->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2209
2210 if (auto *I2P = dyn_cast<IntToPtrInst>(V))
2211 if (Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(I2P->getSrcTy()) <=
2212 Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(I2P->getDestTy()))
2213 return isKnownNonZero(I2P->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2214 }
2215
2216 // Similar to int2ptr above, we can look through ptr2int here if the cast
2217 // is a no-op or an extend and not a truncate.
2218 if (auto *P2I = dyn_cast<PtrToIntInst>(V))
2219 if (Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(P2I->getSrcTy()) <=
2220 Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(P2I->getDestTy()))
2221 return isKnownNonZero(P2I->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2222
2223 unsigned BitWidth = getBitWidth(V->getType()->getScalarType(), Q.DL);
2224
2225 // X | Y != 0 if X != 0 or Y != 0.
2226 Value *X = nullptr, *Y = nullptr;
2227 if (match(V, m_Or(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y))))
2228 return isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q) || isKnownNonZero(Y, Depth, Q);
2229
2230 // ext X != 0 if X != 0.
2231 if (isa<SExtInst>(V) || isa<ZExtInst>(V))
2232 return isKnownNonZero(cast<Instruction>(V)->getOperand(0), Depth, Q);
2233
2234 // shl X, Y != 0 if X is odd. Note that the value of the shift is undefined
2235 // if the lowest bit is shifted off the end.
2236 if (match(V, m_Shl(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) {
2237 // shl nuw can't remove any non-zero bits.
2238 const OverflowingBinaryOperator *BO = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V);
2239 if (Q.IIQ.hasNoUnsignedWrap(BO))
2240 return isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q);
2241
2242 KnownBits Known(BitWidth);
2243 computeKnownBits(X, Known, Depth, Q);
2244 if (Known.One[0])
2245 return true;
2246 }
2247 // shr X, Y != 0 if X is negative. Note that the value of the shift is not
2248 // defined if the sign bit is shifted off the end.
2249 else if (match(V, m_Shr(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) {
2250 // shr exact can only shift out zero bits.
2251 const PossiblyExactOperator *BO = cast<PossiblyExactOperator>(V);
2252 if (BO->isExact())
2253 return isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q);
2254
2255 KnownBits Known = computeKnownBits(X, Depth, Q);
2256 if (Known.isNegative())
2257 return true;
2258
2259 // If the shifter operand is a constant, and all of the bits shifted
2260 // out are known to be zero, and X is known non-zero then at least one
2261 // non-zero bit must remain.
2262 if (ConstantInt *Shift = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Y)) {
2263 auto ShiftVal = Shift->getLimitedValue(BitWidth - 1);
2264 // Is there a known one in the portion not shifted out?
2265 if (Known.countMaxLeadingZeros() < BitWidth - ShiftVal)
2266 return true;
2267 // Are all the bits to be shifted out known zero?
2268 if (Known.countMinTrailingZeros() >= ShiftVal)
2269 return isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q);
2270 }
2271 }
2272 // div exact can only produce a zero if the dividend is zero.
2273 else if (match(V, m_Exact(m_IDiv(m_Value(X), m_Value())))) {
2274 return isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q);
2275 }
2276 // X + Y.
2277 else if (match(V, m_Add(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) {
2278 KnownBits XKnown = computeKnownBits(X, Depth, Q);
2279 KnownBits YKnown = computeKnownBits(Y, Depth, Q);
2280
2281 // If X and Y are both non-negative (as signed values) then their sum is not
2282 // zero unless both X and Y are zero.
2283 if (XKnown.isNonNegative() && YKnown.isNonNegative())
2284 if (isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q) || isKnownNonZero(Y, Depth, Q))
2285 return true;
2286
2287 // If X and Y are both negative (as signed values) then their sum is not
2288 // zero unless both X and Y equal INT_MIN.
2289 if (XKnown.isNegative() && YKnown.isNegative()) {
2290 APInt Mask = APInt::getSignedMaxValue(BitWidth);
2291 // The sign bit of X is set. If some other bit is set then X is not equal
2292 // to INT_MIN.
2293 if (XKnown.One.intersects(Mask))
2294 return true;
2295 // The sign bit of Y is set. If some other bit is set then Y is not equal
2296 // to INT_MIN.
2297 if (YKnown.One.intersects(Mask))
2298 return true;
2299 }
2300
2301 // The sum of a non-negative number and a power of two is not zero.
2302 if (XKnown.isNonNegative() &&
2303 isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(Y, /*OrZero*/ false, Depth, Q))
2304 return true;
2305 if (YKnown.isNonNegative() &&
2306 isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(X, /*OrZero*/ false, Depth, Q))
2307 return true;
2308 }
2309 // X * Y.
2310 else if (match(V, m_Mul(m_Value(X), m_Value(Y)))) {
2311 const OverflowingBinaryOperator *BO = cast<OverflowingBinaryOperator>(V);
2312 // If X and Y are non-zero then so is X * Y as long as the multiplication
2313 // does not overflow.
2314 if ((Q.IIQ.hasNoSignedWrap(BO) || Q.IIQ.hasNoUnsignedWrap(BO)) &&
2315 isKnownNonZero(X, Depth, Q) && isKnownNonZero(Y, Depth, Q))
2316 return true;
2317 }
2318 // (C ? X : Y) != 0 if X != 0 and Y != 0.
2319 else if (const SelectInst *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
2320 if (isKnownNonZero(SI->getTrueValue(), Depth, Q) &&
2321 isKnownNonZero(SI->getFalseValue(), Depth, Q))
2322 return true;
2323 }
2324 // PHI
2325 else if (const PHINode *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
2326 // Try and detect a recurrence that monotonically increases from a
2327 // starting value, as these are common as induction variables.
2328 if (PN->getNumIncomingValues() == 2) {
2329 Value *Start = PN->getIncomingValue(0);
2330 Value *Induction = PN->getIncomingValue(1);
2331 if (isa<ConstantInt>(Induction) && !isa<ConstantInt>(Start))
2332 std::swap(Start, Induction);
2333 if (ConstantInt *C = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Start)) {
2334 if (!C->isZero() && !C->isNegative()) {
2335 ConstantInt *X;
2336 if (Q.IIQ.UseInstrInfo &&
2337 (match(Induction, m_NSWAdd(m_Specific(PN), m_ConstantInt(X))) ||
2338 match(Induction, m_NUWAdd(m_Specific(PN), m_ConstantInt(X)))) &&
2339 !X->isNegative())
2340 return true;
2341 }
2342 }
2343 }
2344 // Check if all incoming values are non-zero constant.
2345 bool AllNonZeroConstants = llvm::all_of(PN->operands(), [](Value *V) {
2346 return isa<ConstantInt>(V) && !cast<ConstantInt>(V)->isZero();
2347 });
2348 if (AllNonZeroConstants)
2349 return true;
2350 }
2351
2352 KnownBits Known(BitWidth);
2353 computeKnownBits(V, Known, Depth, Q);
2354 return Known.One != 0;
2355}
2356
2357/// Return true if V2 == V1 + X, where X is known non-zero.
2358static bool isAddOfNonZero(const Value *V1, const Value *V2, const Query &Q) {
2359 const BinaryOperator *BO = dyn_cast<BinaryOperator>(V1);
2360 if (!BO || BO->getOpcode() != Instruction::Add)
2361 return false;
2362 Value *Op = nullptr;
2363 if (V2 == BO->getOperand(0))
2364 Op = BO->getOperand(1);
2365 else if (V2 == BO->getOperand(1))
2366 Op = BO->getOperand(0);
2367 else
2368 return false;
2369 return isKnownNonZero(Op, 0, Q);
2370}
2371
2372/// Return true if it is known that V1 != V2.
2373static bool isKnownNonEqual(const Value *V1, const Value *V2, const Query &Q) {
2374 if (V1 == V2)
2375 return false;
2376 if (V1->getType() != V2->getType())
2377 // We can't look through casts yet.
2378 return false;
2379 if (isAddOfNonZero(V1, V2, Q) || isAddOfNonZero(V2, V1, Q))
2380 return true;
2381
2382 if (V1->getType()->isIntOrIntVectorTy()) {
2383 // Are any known bits in V1 contradictory to known bits in V2? If V1
2384 // has a known zero where V2 has a known one, they must not be equal.
2385 KnownBits Known1 = computeKnownBits(V1, 0, Q);
2386 KnownBits Known2 = computeKnownBits(V2, 0, Q);
2387
2388 if (Known1.Zero.intersects(Known2.One) ||
2389 Known2.Zero.intersects(Known1.One))
2390 return true;
2391 }
2392 return false;
2393}
2394
2395/// Return true if 'V & Mask' is known to be zero. We use this predicate to
2396/// simplify operations downstream. Mask is known to be zero for bits that V
2397/// cannot have.
2398///
2399/// This function is defined on values with integer type, values with pointer
2400/// type, and vectors of integers. In the case
2401/// where V is a vector, the mask, known zero, and known one values are the
2402/// same width as the vector element, and the bit is set only if it is true
2403/// for all of the elements in the vector.
2404bool MaskedValueIsZero(const Value *V, const APInt &Mask, unsigned Depth,
2405 const Query &Q) {
2406 KnownBits Known(Mask.getBitWidth());
2407 computeKnownBits(V, Known, Depth, Q);
2408 return Mask.isSubsetOf(Known.Zero);
2409}
2410
2411// Match a signed min+max clamp pattern like smax(smin(In, CHigh), CLow).
2412// Returns the input and lower/upper bounds.
2413static bool isSignedMinMaxClamp(const Value *Select, const Value *&In,
2414 const APInt *&CLow, const APInt *&CHigh) {
2415 assert(isa<Operator>(Select) &&
2416 cast<Operator>(Select)->getOpcode() == Instruction::Select &&
2417 "Input should be a Select!");
2418
2419 const Value *LHS, *RHS, *LHS2, *RHS2;
2420 SelectPatternFlavor SPF = matchSelectPattern(Select, LHS, RHS).Flavor;
2421 if (SPF != SPF_SMAX && SPF != SPF_SMIN)
2422 return false;
2423
2424 if (!match(RHS, m_APInt(CLow)))
2425 return false;
2426
2427 SelectPatternFlavor SPF2 = matchSelectPattern(LHS, LHS2, RHS2).Flavor;
2428 if (getInverseMinMaxFlavor(SPF) != SPF2)
2429 return false;
2430
2431 if (!match(RHS2, m_APInt(CHigh)))
2432 return false;
2433
2434 if (SPF == SPF_SMIN)
2435 std::swap(CLow, CHigh);
2436
2437 In = LHS2;
2438 return CLow->sle(*CHigh);
2439}
2440
2441/// For vector constants, loop over the elements and find the constant with the
2442/// minimum number of sign bits. Return 0 if the value is not a vector constant
2443/// or if any element was not analyzed; otherwise, return the count for the
2444/// element with the minimum number of sign bits.
2445static unsigned computeNumSignBitsVectorConstant(const Value *V,
2446 unsigned TyBits) {
2447 const auto *CV = dyn_cast<Constant>(V);
2448 if (!CV || !CV->getType()->isVectorTy())
2449 return 0;
2450
2451 unsigned MinSignBits = TyBits;
2452 unsigned NumElts = CV->getType()->getVectorNumElements();
2453 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
2454 // If we find a non-ConstantInt, bail out.
2455 auto *Elt = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantInt>(CV->getAggregateElement(i));
2456 if (!Elt)
2457 return 0;
2458
2459 MinSignBits = std::min(MinSignBits, Elt->getValue().getNumSignBits());
2460 }
2461
2462 return MinSignBits;
2463}
2464
2465static unsigned ComputeNumSignBitsImpl(const Value *V, unsigned Depth,
2466 const Query &Q);
2467
2468static unsigned ComputeNumSignBits(const Value *V, unsigned Depth,
2469 const Query &Q) {
2470 unsigned Result = ComputeNumSignBitsImpl(V, Depth, Q);
2471 assert(Result > 0 && "At least one sign bit needs to be present!");
2472 return Result;
2473}
2474
2475/// Return the number of times the sign bit of the register is replicated into
2476/// the other bits. We know that at least 1 bit is always equal to the sign bit
2477/// (itself), but other cases can give us information. For example, immediately
2478/// after an "ashr X, 2", we know that the top 3 bits are all equal to each
2479/// other, so we return 3. For vectors, return the number of sign bits for the
2480/// vector element with the minimum number of known sign bits.
2481static unsigned ComputeNumSignBitsImpl(const Value *V, unsigned Depth,
2482 const Query &Q) {
2483 assert(Depth <= MaxDepth && "Limit Search Depth");
2484
2485 // We return the minimum number of sign bits that are guaranteed to be present
2486 // in V, so for undef we have to conservatively return 1. We don't have the
2487 // same behavior for poison though -- that's a FIXME today.
2488
2489 Type *ScalarTy = V->getType()->getScalarType();
2490 unsigned TyBits = ScalarTy->isPointerTy() ?
2491 Q.DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy) :
2492 Q.DL.getTypeSizeInBits(ScalarTy);
2493
2494 unsigned Tmp, Tmp2;
2495 unsigned FirstAnswer = 1;
2496
2497 // Note that ConstantInt is handled by the general computeKnownBits case
2498 // below.
2499
2500 if (Depth == MaxDepth)
2501 return 1; // Limit search depth.
2502
2503 const Operator *U = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
2504 switch (Operator::getOpcode(V)) {
2505 default: break;
2506 case Instruction::SExt:
2507 Tmp = TyBits - U->getOperand(0)->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
2508 return ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q) + Tmp;
2509
2510 case Instruction::SDiv: {
2511 const APInt *Denominator;
2512 // sdiv X, C -> adds log(C) sign bits.
2513 if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(Denominator))) {
2514
2515 // Ignore non-positive denominator.
2516 if (!Denominator->isStrictlyPositive())
2517 break;
2518
2519 // Calculate the incoming numerator bits.
2520 unsigned NumBits = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2521
2522 // Add floor(log(C)) bits to the numerator bits.
2523 return std::min(TyBits, NumBits + Denominator->logBase2());
2524 }
2525 break;
2526 }
2527
2528 case Instruction::SRem: {
2529 const APInt *Denominator;
2530 // srem X, C -> we know that the result is within [-C+1,C) when C is a
2531 // positive constant. This let us put a lower bound on the number of sign
2532 // bits.
2533 if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(Denominator))) {
2534
2535 // Ignore non-positive denominator.
2536 if (!Denominator->isStrictlyPositive())
2537 break;
2538
2539 // Calculate the incoming numerator bits. SRem by a positive constant
2540 // can't lower the number of sign bits.
2541 unsigned NumrBits =
2542 ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2543
2544 // Calculate the leading sign bit constraints by examining the
2545 // denominator. Given that the denominator is positive, there are two
2546 // cases:
2547 //
2548 // 1. the numerator is positive. The result range is [0,C) and [0,C) u<
2549 // (1 << ceilLogBase2(C)).
2550 //
2551 // 2. the numerator is negative. Then the result range is (-C,0] and
2552 // integers in (-C,0] are either 0 or >u (-1 << ceilLogBase2(C)).
2553 //
2554 // Thus a lower bound on the number of sign bits is `TyBits -
2555 // ceilLogBase2(C)`.
2556
2557 unsigned ResBits = TyBits - Denominator->ceilLogBase2();
2558 return std::max(NumrBits, ResBits);
2559 }
2560 break;
2561 }
2562
2563 case Instruction::AShr: {
2564 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2565 // ashr X, C -> adds C sign bits. Vectors too.
2566 const APInt *ShAmt;
2567 if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(ShAmt))) {
2568 if (ShAmt->uge(TyBits))
2569 break; // Bad shift.
2570 unsigned ShAmtLimited = ShAmt->getZExtValue();
2571 Tmp += ShAmtLimited;
2572 if (Tmp > TyBits) Tmp = TyBits;
2573 }
2574 return Tmp;
2575 }
2576 case Instruction::Shl: {
2577 const APInt *ShAmt;
2578 if (match(U->getOperand(1), m_APInt(ShAmt))) {
2579 // shl destroys sign bits.
2580 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2581 if (ShAmt->uge(TyBits) || // Bad shift.
2582 ShAmt->uge(Tmp)) break; // Shifted all sign bits out.
2583 Tmp2 = ShAmt->getZExtValue();
2584 return Tmp - Tmp2;
2585 }
2586 break;
2587 }
2588 case Instruction::And:
2589 case Instruction::Or:
2590 case Instruction::Xor: // NOT is handled here.
2591 // Logical binary ops preserve the number of sign bits at the worst.
2592 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2593 if (Tmp != 1) {
2594 Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
2595 FirstAnswer = std::min(Tmp, Tmp2);
2596 // We computed what we know about the sign bits as our first
2597 // answer. Now proceed to the generic code that uses
2598 // computeKnownBits, and pick whichever answer is better.
2599 }
2600 break;
2601
2602 case Instruction::Select: {
2603 // If we have a clamp pattern, we know that the number of sign bits will be
2604 // the minimum of the clamp min/max range.
2605 const Value *X;
2606 const APInt *CLow, *CHigh;
2607 if (isSignedMinMaxClamp(U, X, CLow, CHigh))
2608 return std::min(CLow->getNumSignBits(), CHigh->getNumSignBits());
2609
2610 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
2611 if (Tmp == 1) break;
2612 Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(2), Depth + 1, Q);
2613 return std::min(Tmp, Tmp2);
2614 }
2615
2616 case Instruction::Add:
2617 // Add can have at most one carry bit. Thus we know that the output
2618 // is, at worst, one more bit than the inputs.
2619 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2620 if (Tmp == 1) break;
2621
2622 // Special case decrementing a value (ADD X, -1):
2623 if (const auto *CRHS = dyn_cast<Constant>(U->getOperand(1)))
2624 if (CRHS->isAllOnesValue()) {
2625 KnownBits Known(TyBits);
2626 computeKnownBits(U->getOperand(0), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
2627
2628 // If the input is known to be 0 or 1, the output is 0/-1, which is all
2629 // sign bits set.
2630 if ((Known.Zero | 1).isAllOnesValue())
2631 return TyBits;
2632
2633 // If we are subtracting one from a positive number, there is no carry
2634 // out of the result.
2635 if (Known.isNonNegative())
2636 return Tmp;
2637 }
2638
2639 Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
2640 if (Tmp2 == 1) break;
2641 return std::min(Tmp, Tmp2)-1;
2642
2643 case Instruction::Sub:
2644 Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
2645 if (Tmp2 == 1) break;
2646
2647 // Handle NEG.
2648 if (const auto *CLHS = dyn_cast<Constant>(U->getOperand(0)))
2649 if (CLHS->isNullValue()) {
2650 KnownBits Known(TyBits);
2651 computeKnownBits(U->getOperand(1), Known, Depth + 1, Q);
2652 // If the input is known to be 0 or 1, the output is 0/-1, which is all
2653 // sign bits set.
2654 if ((Known.Zero | 1).isAllOnesValue())
2655 return TyBits;
2656
2657 // If the input is known to be positive (the sign bit is known clear),
2658 // the output of the NEG has the same number of sign bits as the input.
2659 if (Known.isNonNegative())
2660 return Tmp2;
2661
2662 // Otherwise, we treat this like a SUB.
2663 }
2664
2665 // Sub can have at most one carry bit. Thus we know that the output
2666 // is, at worst, one more bit than the inputs.
2667 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2668 if (Tmp == 1) break;
2669 return std::min(Tmp, Tmp2)-1;
2670
2671 case Instruction::Mul: {
2672 // The output of the Mul can be at most twice the valid bits in the inputs.
2673 unsigned SignBitsOp0 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2674 if (SignBitsOp0 == 1) break;
2675 unsigned SignBitsOp1 = ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
2676 if (SignBitsOp1 == 1) break;
2677 unsigned OutValidBits =
2678 (TyBits - SignBitsOp0 + 1) + (TyBits - SignBitsOp1 + 1);
2679 return OutValidBits > TyBits ? 1 : TyBits - OutValidBits + 1;
2680 }
2681
2682 case Instruction::PHI: {
2683 const PHINode *PN = cast<PHINode>(U);
2684 unsigned NumIncomingValues = PN->getNumIncomingValues();
2685 // Don't analyze large in-degree PHIs.
2686 if (NumIncomingValues > 4) break;
2687 // Unreachable blocks may have zero-operand PHI nodes.
2688 if (NumIncomingValues == 0) break;
2689
2690 // Take the minimum of all incoming values. This can't infinitely loop
2691 // because of our depth threshold.
2692 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(PN->getIncomingValue(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2693 for (unsigned i = 1, e = NumIncomingValues; i != e; ++i) {
2694 if (Tmp == 1) return Tmp;
2695 Tmp = std::min(
2696 Tmp, ComputeNumSignBits(PN->getIncomingValue(i), Depth + 1, Q));
2697 }
2698 return Tmp;
2699 }
2700
2701 case Instruction::Trunc:
2702 // FIXME: it's tricky to do anything useful for this, but it is an important
2703 // case for targets like X86.
2704 break;
2705
2706 case Instruction::ExtractElement:
2707 // Look through extract element. At the moment we keep this simple and skip
2708 // tracking the specific element. But at least we might find information
2709 // valid for all elements of the vector (for example if vector is sign
2710 // extended, shifted, etc).
2711 return ComputeNumSignBits(U->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2712
2713 case Instruction::ShuffleVector: {
2714 // TODO: This is copied almost directly from the SelectionDAG version of
2715 // ComputeNumSignBits. It would be better if we could share common
2716 // code. If not, make sure that changes are translated to the DAG.
2717
2718 // Collect the minimum number of sign bits that are shared by every vector
2719 // element referenced by the shuffle.
2720 auto *Shuf = cast<ShuffleVectorInst>(U);
2721 int NumElts = Shuf->getOperand(0)->getType()->getVectorNumElements();
2722 int NumMaskElts = Shuf->getMask()->getType()->getVectorNumElements();
2723 APInt DemandedLHS(NumElts, 0), DemandedRHS(NumElts, 0);
2724 for (int i = 0; i != NumMaskElts; ++i) {
2725 int M = Shuf->getMaskValue(i);
2726 assert(M < NumElts * 2 && "Invalid shuffle mask constant");
2727 // For undef elements, we don't know anything about the common state of
2728 // the shuffle result.
2729 if (M == -1)
2730 return 1;
2731 if (M < NumElts)
2732 DemandedLHS.setBit(M % NumElts);
2733 else
2734 DemandedRHS.setBit(M % NumElts);
2735 }
2736 Tmp = std::numeric_limits<unsigned>::max();
2737 if (!!DemandedLHS)
2738 Tmp = ComputeNumSignBits(Shuf->getOperand(0), Depth + 1, Q);
2739 if (!!DemandedRHS) {
2740 Tmp2 = ComputeNumSignBits(Shuf->getOperand(1), Depth + 1, Q);
2741 Tmp = std::min(Tmp, Tmp2);
2742 }
2743 // If we don't know anything, early out and try computeKnownBits fall-back.
2744 if (Tmp == 1)
2745 break;
2746 assert(Tmp <= V->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits() &&
2747 "Failed to determine minimum sign bits");
2748 return Tmp;
2749 }
2750 }
2751
2752 // Finally, if we can prove that the top bits of the result are 0's or 1's,
2753 // use this information.
2754
2755 // If we can examine all elements of a vector constant successfully, we're
2756 // done (we can't do any better than that). If not, keep trying.
2757 if (unsigned VecSignBits = computeNumSignBitsVectorConstant(V, TyBits))
2758 return VecSignBits;
2759
2760 KnownBits Known(TyBits);
2761 computeKnownBits(V, Known, Depth, Q);
2762
2763 // If we know that the sign bit is either zero or one, determine the number of
2764 // identical bits in the top of the input value.
2765 return std::max(FirstAnswer, Known.countMinSignBits());
2766}
2767
2768/// This function computes the integer multiple of Base that equals V.
2769/// If successful, it returns true and returns the multiple in
2770/// Multiple. If unsuccessful, it returns false. It looks
2771/// through SExt instructions only if LookThroughSExt is true.
2772bool llvm::ComputeMultiple(Value *V, unsigned Base, Value *&Multiple,
2773 bool LookThroughSExt, unsigned Depth) {
2774 const unsigned MaxDepth = 6;
2775
2776 assert(V && "No Value?");
2777 assert(Depth <= MaxDepth && "Limit Search Depth");
2778 assert(V->getType()->isIntegerTy() && "Not integer or pointer type!");
2779
2780 Type *T = V->getType();
2781
2782 ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(V);
2783
2784 if (Base == 0)
2785 return false;
2786
2787 if (Base == 1) {
2788 Multiple = V;
2789 return true;
2790 }
2791
2792 ConstantExpr *CO = dyn_cast<ConstantExpr>(V);
2793 Constant *BaseVal = ConstantInt::get(T, Base);
2794 if (CO && CO == BaseVal) {
2795 // Multiple is 1.
2796 Multiple = ConstantInt::get(T, 1);
2797 return true;
2798 }
2799
2800 if (CI && CI->getZExtValue() % Base == 0) {
2801 Multiple = ConstantInt::get(T, CI->getZExtValue() / Base);
2802 return true;
2803 }
2804
2805 if (Depth == MaxDepth) return false; // Limit search depth.
2806
2807 Operator *I = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
2808 if (!I) return false;
2809
2810 switch (I->getOpcode()) {
2811 default: break;
2812 case Instruction::SExt:
2813 if (!LookThroughSExt) return false;
2814 // otherwise fall through to ZExt
2815 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
2816 case Instruction::ZExt:
2817 return ComputeMultiple(I->getOperand(0), Base, Multiple,
2818 LookThroughSExt, Depth+1);
2819 case Instruction::Shl:
2820 case Instruction::Mul: {
2821 Value *Op0 = I->getOperand(0);
2822 Value *Op1 = I->getOperand(1);
2823
2824 if (I->getOpcode() == Instruction::Shl) {
2825 ConstantInt *Op1CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Op1);
2826 if (!Op1CI) return false;
2827 // Turn Op0 << Op1 into Op0 * 2^Op1
2828 APInt Op1Int = Op1CI->getValue();
2829 uint64_t BitToSet = Op1Int.getLimitedValue(Op1Int.getBitWidth() - 1);
2830 APInt API(Op1Int.getBitWidth(), 0);
2831 API.setBit(BitToSet);
2832 Op1 = ConstantInt::get(V->getContext(), API);
2833 }
2834
2835 Value *Mul0 = nullptr;
2836 if (ComputeMultiple(Op0, Base, Mul0, LookThroughSExt, Depth+1)) {
2837 if (Constant *Op1C = dyn_cast<Constant>(Op1))
2838 if (Constant *MulC = dyn_cast<Constant>(Mul0)) {
2839 if (Op1C->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits() <
2840 MulC->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits())
2841 Op1C = ConstantExpr::getZExt(Op1C, MulC->getType());
2842 if (Op1C->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits() >
2843 MulC->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits())
2844 MulC = ConstantExpr::getZExt(MulC, Op1C->getType());
2845
2846 // V == Base * (Mul0 * Op1), so return (Mul0 * Op1)
2847 Multiple = ConstantExpr::getMul(MulC, Op1C);
2848 return true;
2849 }
2850
2851 if (ConstantInt *Mul0CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Mul0))
2852 if (Mul0CI->getValue() == 1) {
2853 // V == Base * Op1, so return Op1
2854 Multiple = Op1;
2855 return true;
2856 }
2857 }
2858
2859 Value *Mul1 = nullptr;
2860 if (ComputeMultiple(Op1, Base, Mul1, LookThroughSExt, Depth+1)) {
2861 if (Constant *Op0C = dyn_cast<Constant>(Op0))
2862 if (Constant *MulC = dyn_cast<Constant>(Mul1)) {
2863 if (Op0C->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits() <
2864 MulC->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits())
2865 Op0C = ConstantExpr::getZExt(Op0C, MulC->getType());
2866 if (Op0C->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits() >
2867 MulC->getType()->getPrimitiveSizeInBits())
2868 MulC = ConstantExpr::getZExt(MulC, Op0C->getType());
2869
2870 // V == Base * (Mul1 * Op0), so return (Mul1 * Op0)
2871 Multiple = ConstantExpr::getMul(MulC, Op0C);
2872 return true;
2873 }
2874
2875 if (ConstantInt *Mul1CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Mul1))
2876 if (Mul1CI->getValue() == 1) {
2877 // V == Base * Op0, so return Op0
2878 Multiple = Op0;
2879 return true;
2880 }
2881 }
2882 }
2883 }
2884
2885 // We could not determine if V is a multiple of Base.
2886 return false;
2887}

2889Intrinsic::ID llvm::getIntrinsicForCallSite(ImmutableCallSite ICS,
2890 const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
2891 const Function *F = ICS.getCalledFunction();
2892 if (!F)
2893 return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
2894
2895 if (F->isIntrinsic())
2896 return F->getIntrinsicID();
2897
2898 if (!TLI)
2899 return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
2900
2901 LibFunc Func;
2902 // We're going to make assumptions on the semantics of the functions, check
2903 // that the target knows that it's available in this environment and it does
2904 // not have local linkage.
2905 if (!F || F->hasLocalLinkage() || !TLI->getLibFunc(*F, Func))
2906 return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
2907
2908 if (!ICS.onlyReadsMemory())
2909 return Intrinsic::not_intrinsic;
2910
2911 // Otherwise check if we have a call to a function that can be turned into a
2912 // vector intrinsic.
2913 switch (Func) {
2914 default:
2915 break;
2916 case LibFunc_sin:
2917 case LibFunc_sinf:
2918 case LibFunc_sinl:
2919 return Intrinsic::sin;
2920 case LibFunc_cos:
2921 case LibFunc_cosf:
2922 case LibFunc_cosl:
2923 return Intrinsic::cos;
2924 case LibFunc_exp:
2925 case LibFunc_expf:
2926 case LibFunc_expl:
2927 return Intrinsic::exp;
2928 case LibFunc_exp2:
2929 case LibFunc_exp2f:
2930 case LibFunc_exp2l:
2931 return Intrinsic::exp2;
2932 case LibFunc_log:
2933 case LibFunc_logf:
2934 case LibFunc_logl:
2935 return Intrinsic::log;
2936 case LibFunc_log10:
2937 case LibFunc_log10f:
2938 case LibFunc_log10l:
2939 return Intrinsic::log10;
2940 case LibFunc_log2:
2941 case LibFunc_log2f:
2942 case LibFunc_log2l:
2943 return Intrinsic::log2;
2944 case LibFunc_fabs:
2945 case LibFunc_fabsf:
2946 case LibFunc_fabsl:
2947 return Intrinsic::fabs;
2948 case LibFunc_fmin:
2949 case LibFunc_fminf:
2950 case LibFunc_fminl:
2951 return Intrinsic::minnum;
2952 case LibFunc_fmax:
2953 case LibFunc_fmaxf:
2954 case LibFunc_fmaxl:
2955 return Intrinsic::maxnum;
2956 case LibFunc_copysign:
2957 case LibFunc_copysignf:
2958 case LibFunc_copysignl:
2959 return Intrinsic::copysign;
2960 case LibFunc_floor:
2961 case LibFunc_floorf:
2962 case LibFunc_floorl:
2963 return Intrinsic::floor;
2964 case LibFunc_ceil:
2965 case LibFunc_ceilf:
2966 case LibFunc_ceill:

2968 case LibFunc_trunc:

2997/// Return true if we can prove that the specified FP value is never equal to
2998/// -0.0.
2999///
3000/// NOTE: this function will need to be revisited when we support non-default
3001/// rounding modes!
3002bool llvm::CannotBeNegativeZero(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3003 unsigned Depth) {
3004 if (auto *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V))
3005 return !CFP->getValueAPF().isNegZero();
3006
3007 // Limit search depth.
3008 if (Depth == MaxDepth)
3009 return false;
3010
3011 auto *Op = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
3012 if (!Op)
3013 return false;
3014
3015 // Check if the nsz fast-math flag is set.
3016 if (auto *FPO = dyn_cast<FPMathOperator>(Op))
3017 if (FPO->hasNoSignedZeros())
3018 return true;
3019
3020 // (fadd x, 0.0) is guaranteed to return +0.0, not -0.0.
3021 if (match(Op, m_FAdd(m_Value(), m_PosZeroFP())))
3022 return true;
3023
3024 // sitofp and uitofp turn into +0.0 for zero.
3025 if (isa<SIToFPInst>(Op) || isa<UIToFPInst>(Op))
3026 return true;
3027
3028 if (auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallInst>(Op)) {
3029 Intrinsic::ID IID = getIntrinsicForCallSite(Call, TLI);
3030 switch (IID) {
3031 default:
3032 break;
3033 // sqrt(-0.0) = -0.0, no other negative results are possible.
3034 case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3035 case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
3036 return CannotBeNegativeZero(Call->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3037 // fabs(x) != -0.0
3038 case Intrinsic::fabs:
3039 return true;
3040 }
3041 }
3042
3043 return false;
3044}
3045
3046/// If \p SignBitOnly is true, test for a known 0 sign bit rather than a
3047/// standard ordered compare. e.g. make -0.0 olt 0.0 be true because of the sign
3048/// bit despite comparing equal.
3049static bool cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(const Value *V,
3050 const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3051 bool SignBitOnly,
3052 unsigned Depth) {
3053 // TODO: This function does not do the right thing when SignBitOnly is true
3054 // and we're lowering to a hypothetical IEEE 754-compliant-but-evil platform
3055 // which flips the sign bits of NaNs. See
3056 // https://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=31702.
3057
3058 if (const ConstantFP *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V)) {
3059 return !CFP->getValueAPF().isNegative() ||
3060 (!SignBitOnly && CFP->getValueAPF().isZero());
3061 }
3062
3063 // Handle vector of constants.
3064 if (auto *CV = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
3065 if (CV->getType()->isVectorTy()) {
3066 unsigned NumElts = CV->getType()->getVectorNumElements();
3067 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3068 auto *CFP = dyn_cast_or_null<ConstantFP>(CV->getAggregateElement(i));
3069 if (!CFP)
3070 return false;
3071 if (CFP->getValueAPF().isNegative() &&
3072 (SignBitOnly || !CFP->getValueAPF().isZero()))
3073 return false;
3074 }
3075
3076 // All non-negative ConstantFPs.
3077 return true;
3078 }
3079 }
3080
3081 if (Depth == MaxDepth)
3082 return false; // Limit search depth.
3083
3084 const Operator *I = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
3085 if (!I)
3086 return false;
3087
3088 switch (I->getOpcode()) {
3089 default:
3090 break;
3091 // Unsigned integers are always nonnegative.
3092 case Instruction::UIToFP:
3093 return true;
3094 case Instruction::FMul:
3095 // x*x is always non-negative or a NaN.
3096 if (I->getOperand(0) == I->getOperand(1) &&
3097 (!SignBitOnly || cast<FPMathOperator>(I)->hasNoNaNs()))
3098 return true;
3099
3100 LLVM_FALLTHROUGH;
3101 case Instruction::FAdd:
3102 case Instruction::FDiv:
3103 case Instruction::FRem:
3104 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3105 Depth + 1) &&
3106 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3107 Depth + 1);
3108 case Instruction::Select:
3109 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3110 Depth + 1) &&
3111 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(2), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3112 Depth + 1);
3113 case Instruction::FPExt:
3114 case Instruction::FPTrunc:
3115 // Widening/narrowing never change sign.
3116 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3117 Depth + 1);
3118 case Instruction::ExtractElement:
3119 // Look through extract element. At the moment we keep this simple and skip
3120 // tracking the specific element. But at least we might find information
3121 // valid for all elements of the vector.
3122 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3123 Depth + 1);
3124 case Instruction::Call:
3125 const auto *CI = cast<CallInst>(I);
3126 Intrinsic::ID IID = getIntrinsicForCallSite(CI, TLI);
3127 switch (IID) {
3128 default:
3129 break;
3130 case Intrinsic::maxnum:
3131 return (isKnownNeverNaN(I->getOperand(0), TLI) &&
3132 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI,
3133 SignBitOnly, Depth + 1)) ||
3134 (isKnownNeverNaN(I->getOperand(1), TLI) &&
3135 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI,
3136 SignBitOnly, Depth + 1));
3137
3138 case Intrinsic::maximum:
3139 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3140 Depth + 1) ||
3141 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3142 Depth + 1);
3143 case Intrinsic::minnum:
3144 case Intrinsic::minimum:
3145 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3146 Depth + 1) &&
3147 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(1), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3148 Depth + 1);
3149 case Intrinsic::exp:
3150 case Intrinsic::exp2:
3151 case Intrinsic::fabs:
3152 return true;
3153
3154 case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3155 // sqrt(x) is always >= -0 or NaN. Moreover, sqrt(x) == -0 iff x == -0.
3156 if (!SignBitOnly)
3157 return true;
3158 return CI->hasNoNaNs() && (CI->hasNoSignedZeros() ||
3159 CannotBeNegativeZero(CI->getOperand(0), TLI));
3160
3161 case Intrinsic::powi:
3162 if (ConstantInt *Exponent = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(I->getOperand(1))) {
3163 // powi(x,n) is non-negative if n is even.
3164 if (Exponent->getBitWidth() <= 64 && Exponent->getSExtValue() % 2u == 0)
3165 return true;
3166 }
3167 // TODO: This is not correct. Given that exp is an integer, here are the
3168 // ways that pow can return a negative value:
3169 //
3170 // pow(x, exp) --> negative if exp is odd and x is negative.
3171 // pow(-0, exp) --> -inf if exp is negative odd.
3172 // pow(-0, exp) --> -0 if exp is positive odd.
3173 // pow(-inf, exp) --> -0 if exp is negative odd.
3174 // pow(-inf, exp) --> -inf if exp is positive odd.
3175 //
3176 // Therefore, if !SignBitOnly, we can return true if x >= +0 or x is NaN,
3177 // but we must return false if x == -0. Unfortunately we do not currently
3178 // have a way of expressing this constraint. See details in
3179 // https://llvm.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=31702.
3180 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(0), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3181 Depth + 1);
3182
3183 case Intrinsic::fma:
3184 case Intrinsic::fmuladd:
3185 // x*x+y is non-negative if y is non-negative.
3186 return I->getOperand(0) == I->getOperand(1) &&
3187 (!SignBitOnly || cast<FPMathOperator>(I)->hasNoNaNs()) &&
3188 cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(I->getOperand(2), TLI, SignBitOnly,
3189 Depth + 1);
3190 }
3191 break;
3192 }
3193 return false;
3194}
3195
3196bool llvm::CannotBeOrderedLessThanZero(const Value *V,
3197 const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
3198 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(V, TLI, false, 0);
3199}

3201bool llvm::SignBitMustBeZero(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI) {
3202 return cannotBeOrderedLessThanZeroImpl(V, TLI, true, 0);

3204
3205bool llvm::isKnownNeverNaN(const Value *V, const TargetLibraryInfo *TLI,
3206 unsigned Depth) {
3207 assert(V->getType()->isFPOrFPVectorTy() && "Querying for NaN on non-FP type");
3208
3209 // If we're told that NaNs won't happen, assume they won't.
3210 if (auto *FPMathOp = dyn_cast<FPMathOperator>(V))
3211 if (FPMathOp->hasNoNaNs())
3212 return true;
3213
3214 // Handle scalar constants.
3215 if (auto *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(V))
3216 return !CFP->isNaN();
3217
3218 if (Depth == MaxDepth)
3219 return false;
3220
3221 if (auto *Inst = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V)) {
3222 switch (Inst->getOpcode()) {
3223 case Instruction::FAdd:
3224 case Instruction::FMul:
3225 case Instruction::FSub:
3226 case Instruction::FDiv:
3227 case Instruction::FRem: {
3228 // TODO: Need isKnownNeverInfinity
3229 return false;
3230 }
3231 case Instruction::Select: {
3232 return isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3233 isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(2), TLI, Depth + 1);
3234 }
3235 case Instruction::SIToFP:
3236 case Instruction::UIToFP:
3237 return true;
3238 case Instruction::FPTrunc:
3239 case Instruction::FPExt:
3240 return isKnownNeverNaN(Inst->getOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3241 default:
3242 break;
3243 }
3244 }
3245
3246 if (const auto *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(V)) {
3247 switch (II->getIntrinsicID()) {
3248 case Intrinsic::canonicalize:
3249 case Intrinsic::fabs:
3250 case Intrinsic::copysign:
3251 case Intrinsic::exp:
3252 case Intrinsic::exp2:
3253 case Intrinsic::floor:
3254 case Intrinsic::ceil:
3255 case Intrinsic::trunc:
3256 case Intrinsic::rint:
3257 case Intrinsic::nearbyint:
3258 case Intrinsic::round:
3259 return isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1);
3260 case Intrinsic::sqrt:
3261 return isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) &&
3262 CannotBeOrderedLessThanZero(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI);
3263 case Intrinsic::minnum:
3264 case Intrinsic::maxnum:
3265 // If either operand is not NaN, the result is not NaN.
3266 return isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(0), TLI, Depth + 1) ||
3267 isKnownNeverNaN(II->getArgOperand(1), TLI, Depth + 1);
3268 default:
3269 return false;
3270 }
3271 }
3272
3273 // Bail out for constant expressions, but try to handle vector constants.
3274 if (!V->getType()->isVectorTy() || !isa<Constant>(V))
3275 return false;
3276
3277 // For vectors, verify that each element is not NaN.
3278 unsigned NumElts = V->getType()->getVectorNumElements();
3279 for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumElts; ++i) {
3280 Constant *Elt = cast<Constant>(V)->getAggregateElement(i);
3281 if (!Elt)
3282 return false;
3283 if (isa<UndefValue>(Elt))
3284 continue;
3285 auto *CElt = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(Elt);
3286 if (!CElt || CElt->isNaN())
3287 return false;
3288 }
3289 // All elements were confirmed not-NaN or undefined.
3290 return true;
3291}
3292
3293Value *llvm::isBytewiseValue(Value *V) {
3294
3295 // All byte-wide stores are splatable, even of arbitrary variables.
3296 if (V->getType()->isIntegerTy(8))
3297 return V;
3298
3299 LLVMContext &Ctx = V->getContext();
3300
3301 // Undef don't care.
3302 auto *UndefInt8 = UndefValue::get(Type::getInt8Ty(Ctx));
3303 if (isa<UndefValue>(V))
3304 return UndefInt8;
3305
3306 Constant *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V);
3307 if (!C) {
3308 // Conceptually, we could handle things like:
3309 // %a = zext i8 %X to i16
3310 // %b = shl i16 %a, 8
3311 // %c = or i16 %a, %b
3312 // but until there is an example that actually needs this, it doesn't seem
3313 // worth worrying about.
3314 return nullptr;
3315 }
3316
3317 // Handle 'null' ConstantArrayZero etc.
3318 if (C->isNullValue())
3319 return Constant::getNullValue(Type::getInt8Ty(Ctx));
3320
3321 // Constant floating-point values can be handled as integer values if the
3322 // corresponding integer value is "byteable". An important case is 0.0.
3323 if (ConstantFP *CFP = dyn_cast<ConstantFP>(C)) {
3324 Type *Ty = nullptr;
3325 if (CFP->getType()->isHalfTy())
3326 Ty = Type::getInt16Ty(Ctx);
3327 else if (CFP->getType()->isFloatTy())
3328 Ty = Type::getInt32Ty(Ctx);
3329 else if (CFP->getType()->isDoubleTy())
3330 Ty = Type::getInt64Ty(Ctx);
3331 // Don't handle long double formats, which have strange constraints.
3332 return Ty ? isBytewiseValue(ConstantExpr::getBitCast(CFP, Ty)) : nullptr;
3333 }
3334
3335 // We can handle constant integers that are multiple of 8 bits.
3336 if (ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(C)) {
3337 if (CI->getBitWidth() % 8 == 0) {
3338 assert(CI->getBitWidth() > 8 && "8 bits should be handled above!");
3339 if (!CI->getValue().isSplat(8))
3340 return nullptr;
3341 return ConstantInt::get(Ctx, CI->getValue().trunc(8));
3342 }
3343 }
3344
3345 auto Merge = [&](Value *LHS, Value *RHS) -> Value * {
3346 if (LHS == RHS)
3347 return LHS;
3348 if (!LHS || !RHS)
3349 return nullptr;
3350 if (LHS == UndefInt8)
3351 return RHS;
3352 if (RHS == UndefInt8)
3353 return LHS;
3354 return nullptr;
3355 };
3356
3357 if (ConstantDataSequential *CA = dyn_cast<ConstantDataSequential>(C)) {
3358 Value *Val = UndefInt8;
3359 for (unsigned I = 0, E = CA->getNumElements(); I != E; ++I)
3360 if (!(Val = Merge(Val, isBytewiseValue(CA->getElementAsConstant(I)))))
3361 return nullptr;
3362 return Val;
3363 }
3364
3365 if (isa<ConstantVector>(C)) {
3366 Constant *Splat = cast<ConstantVector>(C)->getSplatValue();
3367 return Splat ? isBytewiseValue(Splat) : nullptr;
3368 }
3369
3370 if (isa<ConstantArray>(C) || isa<ConstantStruct>(C)) {
3371 Value *Val = UndefInt8;
3372 for (unsigned I = 0, E = C->getNumOperands(); I != E; ++I)
3373 if (!(Val = Merge(Val, isBytewiseValue(C->getOperand(I)))))
3374 return nullptr;
3375 return Val;
3376 }
3377
3378 // Don't try to handle the handful of other constants.
3379 return nullptr;
3380}
3381
3382// This is the recursive version of BuildSubAggregate. It takes a few different
3383// arguments. Idxs is the index within the nested struct From that we are
3384// looking at now (which is of type IndexedType). IdxSkip is the number of
3385// indices from Idxs that should be left out when inserting into the resulting
3386// struct. To is the result struct built so far, new insertvalue instructions
3387// build on that.
3388static Value *BuildSubAggregate(Value *From, Value* To, Type *IndexedType,
3389 SmallVectorImpl<unsigned> &Idxs,
3390 unsigned IdxSkip,
3391 Instruction *InsertBefore) {
3392 StructType *STy = dyn_cast<StructType>(IndexedType);
3393 if (STy) {
3394 // Save the original To argument so we can modify it
3395 Value *OrigTo = To;
3396 // General case, the type indexed by Idxs is a struct
3397 for (unsigned i = 0, e = STy->getNumElements(); i != e; ++i) {
3398 // Process each struct element recursively
3399 Idxs.push_back(i);
3400 Value *PrevTo = To;
3401 To = BuildSubAggregate(From, To, STy->getElementType(i), Idxs, IdxSkip,
3402 InsertBefore);
3403 Idxs.pop_back();
3404 if (!To) {
3405 // Couldn't find any inserted value for this index? Cleanup
3406 while (PrevTo != OrigTo) {
3407 InsertValueInst* Del = cast<InsertValueInst>(PrevTo);
3408 PrevTo = Del->getAggregateOperand();
3409 Del->eraseFromParent();
3410 }
3411 // Stop processing elements
3412 break;
3413 }
3414 }
3415 // If we successfully found a value for each of our subaggregates
3416 if (To)
3417 return To;
3418 }
3419 // Base case, the type indexed by SourceIdxs is not a struct, or not all of
3420 // the struct's elements had a value that was inserted directly. In the latter
3421 // case, perhaps we can't determine each of the subelements individually, but
3422 // we might be able to find the complete struct somewhere.
3423
3424 // Find the value that is at that particular spot
3425 Value *V = FindInsertedValue(From, Idxs);
3426
3427 if (!V)
3428 return nullptr;
3429
3430 // Insert the value in the new (sub) aggregate
3431 return InsertValueInst::Create(To, V, makeArrayRef(Idxs).slice(IdxSkip),
3432 "tmp", InsertBefore);
3433}
3434
3435// This helper takes a nested struct and extracts a part of it (which is again a
3436// struct) into a new value. For example, given the struct:
3437// { a, { b, { c, d }, e } }
3438// and the indices "1, 1" this returns
3439// { c, d }.
3440//
3441// It does this by inserting an insertvalue for each element in the resulting
3442// struct, as opposed to just inserting a single struct. This will only work if
3443// each of the elements of the substruct are known (ie, inserted into From by an
3444// insertvalue instruction somewhere).
3445//
3446// All inserted insertvalue instructions are inserted before InsertBefore
3447static Value *BuildSubAggregate(Value *From, ArrayRef<unsigned> idx_range,
3448 Instruction *InsertBefore) {
3449 assert(InsertBefore && "Must have someplace to insert!");
3450 Type *IndexedType = ExtractValueInst::getIndexedType(From->getType(),
3451 idx_range);
3452 Value *To = UndefValue::get(IndexedType);
3453 SmallVector<unsigned, 10> Idxs(idx_range.begin(), idx_range.end());
3454 unsigned IdxSkip = Idxs.size();
3455
3456 return BuildSubAggregate(From, To, IndexedType, Idxs, IdxSkip, InsertBefore);
3457}
3458
3459/// Given an aggregate and a sequence of indices, see if the scalar value
3460/// indexed is already around as a register, for example if it was inserted
3461/// directly into the aggregate.
3462///
3463/// If InsertBefore is not null, this function will duplicate (modified)
3464/// insertvalues when a part of a nested struct is extracted.
3465Value *llvm::FindInsertedValue(Value *V, ArrayRef<unsigned> idx_range,
3466 Instruction *InsertBefore) {
3467 // Nothing to index? Just return V then (this is useful at the end of our
3468 // recursion).
3469 if (idx_range.empty())
3470 return V;
3471 // We have indices, so V should have an indexable type.
3472 assert((V->getType()->isStructTy() || V->getType()->isArrayTy()) &&
3473 "Not looking at a struct or array?");
3474 assert(ExtractValueInst::getIndexedType(V->getType(), idx_range) &&
3475 "Invalid indices for type?");
3476
3477 if (Constant *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(V)) {
3478 C = C->getAggregateElement(idx_range[0]);
3479 if (!C) return nullptr;
3480 return FindInsertedValue(C, idx_range.slice(1), InsertBefore);
3481 }
3482
3483 if (InsertValueInst *I = dyn_cast<InsertValueInst>(V)) {
3484 // Loop the indices for the insertvalue instruction in parallel with the
3485 // requested indices
3486 const unsigned *req_idx = idx_range.begin();
3487 for (const unsigned *i = I->idx_begin(), *e = I->idx_end();
3488 i != e; ++i, ++req_idx) {
3489 if (req_idx == idx_range.end()) {
3490 // We can't handle this without inserting insertvalues
3491 if (!InsertBefore)
3492 return nullptr;
3493
3494 // The requested index identifies a part of a nested aggregate. Handle
3495 // this specially. For example,
3496 // %A = insertvalue { i32, {i32, i32 } } undef, i32 10, 1, 0
3497 // %B = insertvalue { i32, {i32, i32 } } %A, i32 11, 1, 1
3498 // %C = extractvalue {i32, { i32, i32 } } %B, 1
3499 // This can be changed into
3500 // %A = insertvalue {i32, i32 } undef, i32 10, 0
3501 // %C = insertvalue {i32, i32 } %A, i32 11, 1
3502 // which allows the unused 0,0 element from the nested struct to be
3503 // removed.
3504 return BuildSubAggregate(V, makeArrayRef(idx_range.begin(), req_idx),
3505 InsertBefore);
3506 }
3507
3508 // This insert value inserts something else than what we are looking for.
3509 // See if the (aggregate) value inserted into has the value we are
3510 // looking for, then.
3511 if (*req_idx != *i)
3512 return FindInsertedValue(I->getAggregateOperand(), idx_range,
3513 InsertBefore);
3514 }
3515 // If we end up here, the indices of the insertvalue match with those
3516 // requested (though possibly only partially). Now we recursively look at
3517 // the inserted value, passing any remaining indices.
3518 return FindInsertedValue(I->getInsertedValueOperand(),
3519 makeArrayRef(req_idx, idx_range.end()),
3520 InsertBefore);
3521 }
3522
3523 if (ExtractValueInst *I = dyn_cast<ExtractValueInst>(V)) {
3524 // If we're extracting a value from an aggregate that was extracted from
3525 // something else, we can extract from that something else directly instead.
3526 // However, we will need to chain I's indices with the requested indices.
3527
3528 // Calculate the number of indices required
3529 unsigned size = I->getNumIndices() + idx_range.size();
3530 // Allocate some space to put the new indices in
3531 SmallVector<unsigned, 5> Idxs;
3532 Idxs.reserve(size);
3533 // Add indices from the extract value instruction
3534 Idxs.append(I->idx_begin(), I->idx_end());
3535
3536 // Add requested indices
3537 Idxs.append(idx_range.begin(), idx_range.end());
3538
3539 assert(Idxs.size() == size
3540 && "Number of indices added not correct?");
3541
3542 return FindInsertedValue(I->getAggregateOperand(), Idxs, InsertBefore);
3543 }
3544 // Otherwise, we don't know (such as, extracting from a function return value
3545 // or load instruction)
3546 return nullptr;
3547}
3548
3549/// Analyze the specified pointer to see if it can be expressed as a base
3550/// pointer plus a constant offset. Return the base and offset to the caller.
3551Value *llvm::GetPointerBaseWithConstantOffset(Value *Ptr, int64_t &Offset,
3552 const DataLayout &DL) {
3553 unsigned BitWidth = DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(Ptr->getType());
3554 APInt ByteOffset(BitWidth, 0);
3555
3556 // We walk up the defs but use a visited set to handle unreachable code. In
3557 // that case, we stop after accumulating the cycle once (not that it
3558 // matters).
3559 SmallPtrSet<Value *, 16> Visited;
3560 while (Visited.insert(Ptr).second) {
3561 if (Ptr->getType()->isVectorTy())
3562 break;
3563
3564 if (GEPOperator *GEP = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(Ptr)) {
3565 // If one of the values we have visited is an addrspacecast, then
3566 // the pointer type of this GEP may be different from the type
3567 // of the Ptr parameter which was passed to this function. This
3568 // means when we construct GEPOffset, we need to use the size
3569 // of GEP's pointer type rather than the size of the original
3570 // pointer type.
3571 APInt GEPOffset(DL.getIndexTypeSizeInBits(Ptr->getType()), 0);
3572 if (!GEP->accumulateConstantOffset(DL, GEPOffset))
3573 break;
3574
3575 APInt OrigByteOffset(ByteOffset);
3576 ByteOffset += GEPOffset.sextOrTrunc(ByteOffset.getBitWidth());
3577 if (ByteOffset.getMinSignedBits() > 64) {
3578 // Stop traversal if the pointer offset wouldn't fit into int64_t
3579 // (this should be removed if Offset is updated to an APInt)
3580 ByteOffset = OrigByteOffset;
3581 break;
3582 }
3583
3584 Ptr = GEP->getPointerOperand();
3585 } else if (Operator::getOpcode(Ptr) == Instruction::BitCast ||
3586 Operator::getOpcode(Ptr) == Instruction::AddrSpaceCast) {
3587 Ptr = cast<Operator>(Ptr)->getOperand(0);
3588 } else if (GlobalAlias *GA = dyn_cast<GlobalAlias>(Ptr)) {
3589 if (GA->isInterposable())
3590 break;
3591 Ptr = GA->getAliasee();
3592 } else {
3593 break;
3594 }
3595 }
3596 Offset = ByteOffset.getSExtValue();
3597 return Ptr;
3598}
3599
3600bool llvm::isGEPBasedOnPointerToString(const GEPOperator *GEP,
3601 unsigned CharSize) {
3602 // Make sure the GEP has exactly three arguments.
3603 if (GEP->getNumOperands() != 3)
3604 return false;
3605
3606 // Make sure the index-ee is a pointer to array of \p CharSize integers.
3607 // CharSize.
3608 ArrayType *AT = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(GEP->getSourceElementType());
3609 if (!AT || !AT->getElementType()->isIntegerTy(CharSize))
3610 return false;
3611
3612 // Check to make sure that the first operand of the GEP is an integer and
3613 // has value 0 so that we are sure we're indexing into the initializer.
3614 const ConstantInt *FirstIdx = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(GEP->getOperand(1));
3615 if (!FirstIdx || !FirstIdx->isZero())
3616 return false;
3617
3618 return true;
3619}
3620
3621bool llvm::getConstantDataArrayInfo(const Value *V,
3622 ConstantDataArraySlice &Slice,
3623 unsigned ElementSize, uint64_t Offset) {
3624 assert(V);
3625
3626 // Look through bitcast instructions and geps.
3627 V = V->stripPointerCasts();
3628
3629 // If the value is a GEP instruction or constant expression, treat it as an
3630 // offset.
3631 if (const GEPOperator *GEP = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(V)) {
3632 // The GEP operator should be based on a pointer to string constant, and is
3633 // indexing into the string constant.
3634 if (!isGEPBasedOnPointerToString(GEP, ElementSize))
3635 return false;
3636
3637 // If the second index isn't a ConstantInt, then this is a variable index
3638 // into the array. If this occurs, we can't say anything meaningful about
3639 // the string.
3640 uint64_t StartIdx = 0;
3641 if (const ConstantInt *CI = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(GEP->getOperand(2)))
3642 StartIdx = CI->getZExtValue();
3643 else
3644 return false;
3645 return getConstantDataArrayInfo(GEP->getOperand(0), Slice, ElementSize,
3646 StartIdx + Offset);
3647 }
3648
3649 // The GEP instruction, constant or instruction, must reference a global
3650 // variable that is a constant and is initialized. The referenced constant
3651 // initializer is the array that we'll use for optimization.
3652 const GlobalVariable *GV = dyn_cast<GlobalVariable>(V);
3653 if (!GV || !GV->isConstant() || !GV->hasDefinitiveInitializer())
3654 return false;
3655
3656 const ConstantDataArray *Array;
3657 ArrayType *ArrayTy;
3658 if (GV->getInitializer()->isNullValue()) {
3659 Type *GVTy = GV->getValueType();
3660 if ( (ArrayTy = dyn_cast<ArrayType>(GVTy)) ) {
3661 // A zeroinitializer for the array; there is no ConstantDataArray.
3662 Array = nullptr;
3663 } else {
3664 const DataLayout &DL = GV->getParent()->getDataLayout();
3665 uint64_t SizeInBytes = DL.getTypeStoreSize(GVTy);
3666 uint64_t Length = SizeInBytes / (ElementSize / 8);
3667 if (Length <= Offset)
3668 return false;
3669
3670 Slice.Array = nullptr;
3671 Slice.Offset = 0;
3672 Slice.Length = Length - Offset;
3673 return true;
3674 }
3675 } else {
3676 // This must be a ConstantDataArray.
3677 Array = dyn_cast<ConstantDataArray>(GV->getInitializer());
3678 if (!Array)
3679 return false;
3680 ArrayTy = Array->getType();
3681 }
3682 if (!ArrayTy->getElementType()->isIntegerTy(ElementSize))
3683 return false;
3684
3685 uint64_t NumElts = ArrayTy->getArrayNumElements();
3686 if (Offset > NumElts)
3687 return false;
3688
3689 Slice.Array = Array;
3690 Slice.Offset = Offset;
3691 Slice.Length = NumElts - Offset;
3692 return true;
3693}
3694
3695/// This function computes the length of a null-terminated C string pointed to
3696/// by V. If successful, it returns true and returns the string in Str.
3697/// If unsuccessful, it returns false.
3698bool llvm::getConstantStringInfo(const Value *V, StringRef &Str,
3699 uint64_t Offset, bool TrimAtNul) {
3700 ConstantDataArraySlice Slice;
3701 if (!getConstantDataArrayInfo(V, Slice, 8, Offset))
3702 return false;
3703
3704 if (Slice.Array == nullptr) {
3705 if (TrimAtNul) {
3706 Str = StringRef();
3707 return true;
3708 }
3709 if (Slice.Length == 1) {
3710 Str = StringRef("", 1);
3711 return true;
3712 }
3713 // We cannot instantiate a StringRef as we do not have an appropriate string
3714 // of 0s at hand.
3715 return false;
3716 }
3717
3718 // Start out with the entire array in the StringRef.
3719 Str = Slice.Array->getAsString();
3720 // Skip over 'offset' bytes.
3721 Str = Str.substr(Slice.Offset);
3722
3723 if (TrimAtNul) {
3724 // Trim off the \0 and anything after it. If the array is not nul
3725 // terminated, we just return the whole end of string. The client may know
3726 // some other way that the string is length-bound.
3727 Str = Str.substr(0, Str.find('\0'));
3728 }
3729 return true;
3730}
3731
3732// These next two are very similar to the above, but also look through PHI
3733// nodes.
3734// TODO: See if we can integrate these two together.
3735
3736/// If we can compute the length of the string pointed to by
3737/// the specified pointer, return 'len+1'. If we can't, return 0.
3738static uint64_t GetStringLengthH(const Value *V,
3739 SmallPtrSetImpl<const PHINode*> &PHIs,
3740 unsigned CharSize) {
3741 // Look through noop bitcast instructions.
3742 V = V->stripPointerCasts();
3743
3744 // If this is a PHI node, there are two cases: either we have already seen it
3745 // or we haven't.
3746 if (const PHINode *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(V)) {
3747 if (!PHIs.insert(PN).second)
3748 return ~0ULL; // already in the set.
3749
3750 // If it was new, see if all the input strings are the same length.
3751 uint64_t LenSoFar = ~0ULL;
3752 for (Value *IncValue : PN->incoming_values()) {
3753 uint64_t Len = GetStringLengthH(IncValue, PHIs, CharSize);
3754 if (Len == 0) return 0; // Unknown length -> unknown.
3755
3756 if (Len == ~0ULL) continue;
3757
3758 if (Len != LenSoFar && LenSoFar != ~0ULL)
3759 return 0; // Disagree -> unknown.
3760 LenSoFar = Len;
3761 }
3762
3763 // Success, all agree.
3764 return LenSoFar;
3765 }
3766
3767 // strlen(select(c,x,y)) -> strlen(x) ^ strlen(y)
3768 if (const SelectInst *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(V)) {
3769 uint64_t Len1 = GetStringLengthH(SI->getTrueValue(), PHIs, CharSize);
3770 if (Len1 == 0) return 0;
3771 uint64_t Len2 = GetStringLengthH(SI->getFalseValue(), PHIs, CharSize);
3772 if (Len2 == 0) return 0;
3773 if (Len1 == ~0ULL) return Len2;
3774 if (Len2 == ~0ULL) return Len1;
3775 if (Len1 != Len2) return 0;
3776 return Len1;
3777 }
3778
3779 // Otherwise, see if we can read the string.
3780 ConstantDataArraySlice Slice;
3781 if (!getConstantDataArrayInfo(V, Slice, CharSize))
3782 return 0;
3783
3784 if (Slice.Array == nullptr)
3785 return 1;
3786
3787 // Search for nul characters
3788 unsigned NullIndex = 0;
3789 for (unsigned E = Slice.Length; NullIndex < E; ++NullIndex) {
3790 if (Slice.Array->getElementAsInteger(Slice.Offset + NullIndex) == 0)
3791 break;
3792 }
3793
3794 return NullIndex + 1;
3795}
3796
3797/// If we can compute the length of the string pointed to by
3798/// the specified pointer, return 'len+1'. If we can't, return 0.
3799uint64_t llvm::GetStringLength(const Value *V, unsigned CharSize) {
3800 if (!V->getType()->isPointerTy())
3801 return 0;
3802
3803 SmallPtrSet<const PHINode*, 32> PHIs;
3804 uint64_t Len = GetStringLengthH(V, PHIs, CharSize);
3805 // If Len is ~0ULL, we had an infinite phi cycle: this is dead code, so return
3806 // an empty string as a length.
3807 return Len == ~0ULL ? 1 : Len;
3808}

3810const Value *llvm::getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer(const CallBase *Call) {
3811 assert(Call &&
3812 "getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer only works on nonnull calls");
3813 if (const Value *RV = Call->getReturnedArgOperand())
3814 return RV;
3815 // This can be used only as a aliasing property.
3816 if (isIntrinsicReturningPointerAliasingArgumentWithoutCapturing(Call))
3817 return Call->getArgOperand(0);
3818 return nullptr;
3819}
3820
3821bool llvm::isIntrinsicReturningPointerAliasingArgumentWithoutCapturing(
3822 const CallBase *Call) {
3823 // A CHERI inc-offset of zero aliases the input argument
3824 if (Call->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::cheri_cap_offset_increment) {
3825 if (ConstantInt *C = dyn_cast<ConstantInt>(Call->getOperand(1))) {
3826 return C->isZeroValue();
3827 }
3828 }
3829 // NOTE: we can't return this for setbounds even though the resulting pointer
3830 // aliases with the target, but it might not grant access to the last few
3831 // bytes. If we return true here for setbounds, then GVN will remove some
3832 // loads that would have trapped at runtime. See cheri-intrinisics.ll test.
3833 return /* Call->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::cheri_cap_bounds_set ||
3834 Call->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::cheri_cap_bounds_set_exact ||
3835 Call->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::cheri_bounded_stack_cap || */
3836 Call->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::launder_invariant_group ||
3837 Call->getIntrinsicID() == Intrinsic::strip_invariant_group;
3838}

3840/// \p PN defines a loop-variant pointer to an object. Check if the
3841/// previous iteration of the loop was referring to the same object as \p PN.
3842static bool isSameUnderlyingObjectInLoop(const PHINode *PN,
3843 const LoopInfo *LI) {
3844 // Find the loop-defined value.
3845 Loop *L = LI->getLoopFor(PN->getParent());
3846 if (PN->getNumIncomingValues() != 2)
3847 return true;
3848
3849 // Find the value from previous iteration.
3850 auto *PrevValue = dyn_cast<Instruction>(PN->getIncomingValue(0));
3851 if (!PrevValue || LI->getLoopFor(PrevValue->getParent()) != L)
3852 PrevValue = dyn_cast<Instruction>(PN->getIncomingValue(1));
3853 if (!PrevValue || LI->getLoopFor(PrevValue->getParent()) != L)
3854 return true;
3855
3856 // If a new pointer is loaded in the loop, the pointer references a different
3857 // object in every iteration. E.g.:
3858 // for (i)
3859 // int *p = a[i];
3860 // ...
3861 if (auto *Load = dyn_cast<LoadInst>(PrevValue))
3862 if (!L->isLoopInvariant(Load->getPointerOperand()))
3863 return false;
3864 return true;
3865}
3866
3867Value *llvm::GetUnderlyingObject(Value *V, const DataLayout &DL,
3868 unsigned MaxLookup) {
3869 if (!V->getType()->isPointerTy())
3870 return V;
3871 for (unsigned Count = 0; MaxLookup == 0 || Count < MaxLookup; ++Count) {
3872 if (GEPOperator *GEP = dyn_cast<GEPOperator>(V)) {
3873 V = GEP->getPointerOperand();
3874 } else if (Operator::getOpcode(V) == Instruction::BitCast ||
3875 Operator::getOpcode(V) == Instruction::AddrSpaceCast) {
3876 V = cast<Operator>(V)->getOperand(0);
3877 } else if (GlobalAlias *GA = dyn_cast<GlobalAlias>(V)) {
3878 if (GA->isInterposable())
3879 return V;
3880 V = GA->getAliasee();
3881 } else if (isa<AllocaInst>(V)) {
3882 // An alloca can't be further simplified.
3883 return V;
3884 } else {
3885 if (auto *Call = dyn_cast<CallBase>(V)) {
3886 // CaptureTracking can know about special capturing properties of some
3887 // intrinsics like launder.invariant.group, that can't be expressed with
3888 // the attributes, but have properties like returning aliasing pointer.
3889 // Because some analysis may assume that nocaptured pointer is not
3890 // returned from some special intrinsic (because function would have to
3891 // be marked with returns attribute), it is crucial to use this function
3892 // because it should be in sync with CaptureTracking. Not using it may
3893 // cause weird miscompilations where 2 aliasing pointers are assumed to
3894 // noalias.
3895 if (auto *RP = getArgumentAliasingToReturnedPointer(Call)) {
3896 V = RP;
3897 continue;
3898 }
3899 }
3900
3901 // See if InstructionSimplify knows any relevant tricks.
3902 if (Instruction *I = dyn_cast<Instruction>(V))
3903 // TODO: Acquire a DominatorTree and AssumptionCache and use them.
3904 if (Value *Simplified = SimplifyInstruction(I, {DL, I})) {
3905 V = Simplified;
3906 continue;
3907 }
3908
3909 return V;
3910 }
3911 assert(V->getType()->isPointerTy() && "Unexpected operand type!");
3912 }
3913 return V;
3914}
3915
3916void llvm::GetUnderlyingObjects(const Value *V,
3917 SmallVectorImpl<const Value *> &Objects,
3918 const DataLayout &DL, LoopInfo *LI,
3919 unsigned MaxLookup) {
3920 SmallPtrSet<const Value *, 4> Visited;
3921 SmallVector<const Value *, 4> Worklist;
3922 Worklist.push_back(V);
3923 do {
3924 const Value *P = Worklist.pop_back_val();
3925 P = GetUnderlyingObject(P, DL, MaxLookup);
3926
3927 if (!Visited.insert(P).second)
3928 continue;
3929
3930 if (auto *SI = dyn_cast<SelectInst>(P)) {
3931 Worklist.push_back(SI->getTrueValue());
3932 Worklist.push_back(SI->getFalseValue());
3933 continue;
3934 }
3935
3936 if (auto *PN = dyn_cast<PHINode>(P)) {
3937 // If this PHI changes the underlying object in every iteration of the
3938 // loop, don't look through it. Consider:
3939 // int **A;
3940 // for (i) {
3941 // Prev = Curr; // Prev = PHI (Prev_0, Curr)
3942 // Curr = A[i];
3943 // *Prev, *Curr;
3944 //
3945 // Prev is tracking Curr one iteration behind so they refer to different
3946 // underlying objects.
3947 if (!LI || !LI->isLoopHeader(PN->getParent()) ||
3948 isSameUnderlyingObjectInLoop(PN, LI))
3949 for (Value *IncValue : PN->incoming_values())
3950 Worklist.push_back(IncValue);
3951 continue;
3952 }
3953
3954 Objects.push_back(P);
3955 } while (!Worklist.empty());
3956}

3958/// This is the function that does the work of looking through basic
3959/// ptrtoint+arithmetic+inttoptr sequences.
3960static const Value *getUnderlyingObjectFromInt(const Value *V) {
3961 do {
3962 if (const Operator *U = dyn_cast<Operator>(V)) {
3963 // If we find a ptrtoint, we can transfer control back to the
3964 // regular getUnderlyingObjectFromInt.
3965 if (U->getOpcode() == Instruction::PtrToInt)
3966 return U->getOperand(0);
3967 // If we find an add of a constant, a multiplied value, or a phi, it's
3968 // likely that the other operand will lead us to the base
3969 // object. We don't have to worry about the case where the
3970 // object address is somehow being computed by the multiply,
3971 // because our callers only care when the result is an
3972 // identifiable object.
3973 if (U->getOpcode() != Instruction::Add ||
3974 (!isa<ConstantInt>(U->getOperand(1)) &&
3975 Operator::getOpcode(U->getOperand(1)) != Instruction::Mul &&
3976 !isa<PHINode>(U->getOperand(1))))
3977 return V;
3978 V = U->getOperand(0);
3979 } else {
3980 return V;
3981 }
3982 assert(V->getType()->isIntegerTy() && "Unexpected operand type!");
3983 } while (true);
3984}

3986/// This is a wrapper around GetUnderlyingObjects and adds support for basic
3987/// ptrtoint+arithmetic+inttoptr sequences.
3988/// It returns false if unidentified object is found in GetUnderlyingObjects.
3989bool llvm::getUnderlyingObjectsForCodeGen(const Value *V,
3990 SmallVectorImpl<Value *> &Objects,
3991 const DataLayout &DL) {
3992 SmallPtrSet<const Value *, 16> Visited;
3993 SmallVector<const Value *, 4> Working(1, V);
3994 do {
3995 V = Working.pop_back_val();
3996
3997 SmallVector<const Value *, 4> Objs;
3998 GetUnderlyingObjects(V, Objs, DL);
3999
4000 for (const Value *V : Objs) {
4001 if (!Visited.insert(V).second)
4002 continue;
4003 if (Operator::getOpcode(V) == Instruction::IntToPtr) {
4004 const Value *O =
4005 getUnderlyingObjectFromInt(cast<User>(V)->getOperand(0));
4006 if (O->getType()->isPointerTy()) {
4007 Working.push_back(O);
4008 continue;
4009 }
4010 }
4011 // If GetUnderlyingObjects fails to find an identifiable object,
4012 // getUnderlyingObjectsForCodeGen also fails for safety.
4013 if (!isIdentifiedObject(V)) {
4014 Objects.clear();
4015 return false;
4016 }
4017 Objects.push_back(const_cast<Value *>(V));
4018 }
4019 } while (!Working.empty());
4020 return true;
4021}

4023/// Return true if the only users of this pointer are lifetime markers.
4024bool llvm::onlyUsedByLifetimeMarkers(const Value *V) {
4025 for (const User *U : V->users()) {
4026 const IntrinsicInst *II = dyn_cast<IntrinsicInst>(U);
4027 if (!II) return false;

4029 if (!II->isLifetimeStartOrEnd())
4030 return false;
4031 }

4034
4035bool llvm::isSafeToSpeculativelyExecute(const Value *V,
4036 const Instruction *CtxI,
4037 const DominatorTree *DT) {
4038 const Operator *Inst = dyn_cast<Operator>(V);
4039 if (!Inst)
4040 return false;
4041
4042 for (unsigned i = 0, e = Inst->getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i)
4043 if (Constant *C = dyn_cast<Constant>(Inst->getOperand(i)))
4044 if (C->canTrap())
4045 return false;
4046
4047 switch (Inst->getOpcode()) {
4048 default:
4049 return true;
4050 case Instruction::UDiv:
4051 case Instruction::URem: {
4052 // x / y is undefined if y == 0.
4053 const APInt *V;
4054 if (match(Inst->getOperand(1), m_APInt(V)))
4055 return *V != 0;
4056 return false;
4057 }
4058 case Instruction::SDiv:
4059 case Instruction::SRem: {
4060 // x / y is undefined if y == 0 or x == INT_MIN and y == -1
4061 const APInt *Numerator, *Denominator;
4062 if (!match(Inst->getOperand(1), m_APInt(Denominator)))
4063 return false;
4064 // We cannot hoist this division if the denominator is 0.
4065 if (*Denominator == 0)
4066 return false;
4067 // It's safe to hoist if the denominator is not 0 or -1.
4068 if (*Denominator != -1)
4069 return true;
4070 // At this point we know that the denominator is -1. It is safe to hoist as
4071 // long we know that the numerator is not INT_MIN.
4072 if (match(Inst->getOperand(0), m_APInt(Numerator)))
4073 return !Numerator->isMinSignedValue();
4074 // The numerator *might* be MinSignedValue.
4075 return false;
4076 }
4077 case Instruction::Load: {
4078 const LoadInst *LI = cast<LoadInst>(Inst);
4079 if (!LI->isUnordered() ||
4080 // Speculative load may create a race that did not exist in the source.
4081 LI->getFunction()->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::SanitizeThread) ||
4082 // Speculative load may load data from dirty regions.
4083 LI->getFunction()->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::SanitizeAddress) ||
4084 LI->getFunction()->hasFnAttribute(Attribute::SanitizeHWAddress))
4085 return false;
4086 const DataLayout &DL = LI->getModule()->getDataLayout();
4087 return isDereferenceableAndAlignedPointer(LI->getPointerOperand(),
4088 LI->getAlignment(), DL, CtxI, DT);
4089 }
4090 case Instruction::Call: {
4091 auto *CI = cast<const CallInst>(Inst);
4092 const Function *Callee = CI->getCalledFunction();
4093
4094 // The called function could have undefined behavior or side-effects, even
4095 // if marked readnone nounwind.
4096 return Callee && Callee->isSpeculatable();
4097 }
4098 case Instruction::VAArg:
4099 case Instruction::Alloca:
4100 case Instruction::Invoke:
4101 case Instruction::CallBr:
4102 case Instruction::PHI:
4103 case Instruction::Store:
4104 case Instruction::Ret:
4105 case Instruction::Br:
4106 case Instruction::IndirectBr:
4107 case Instruction::Switch:
4108 case Instruction::Unreachable:
4109 case Instruction::Fence:
4110 case Instruction::AtomicRMW:
4111 case Instruction::AtomicCmpXchg:
4112 case Instruction::LandingPad:
4113 case Instruction::Resume:
4114 case Instruction::CatchSwitch:
4115 case Instruction::CatchPad:
4116 case Instruction::CatchRet:
4117 case Instruction::CleanupPad:
4118 case Instruction::CleanupRet:
4119 return false; // Misc instructions which have effects
4120 }
4121}

4127/// Convert ConstantRange OverflowResult into ValueTracking OverflowResult.
4128static OverflowResult mapOverflowResult(ConstantRange::OverflowResult OR) {
4129 switch (OR) {
4130 case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::MayOverflow:
4131 return OverflowResult::MayOverflow;
4132 case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsLow:
4133 return OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsLow;
4134 case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsHigh:
4135 return OverflowResult::AlwaysOverflowsHigh;
4136 case ConstantRange::OverflowResult::NeverOverflows:
4137 return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
4138 }
4139 llvm_unreachable("Unknown OverflowResult");
4140}

4142/// Combine constant ranges from computeConstantRange() and computeKnownBits().
4143static ConstantRange computeConstantRangeIncludingKnownBits(
4144 const Value *V, bool ForSigned, const DataLayout &DL, unsigned Depth,
4145 AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI, const DominatorTree *DT,
4146 OptimizationRemarkEmitter *ORE = nullptr, bool UseInstrInfo = true) {
4147 KnownBits Known = computeKnownBits(
4148 V, DL, Depth, AC, CxtI, DT, ORE, UseInstrInfo);
4149 ConstantRange CR1 = ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(Known, ForSigned);
4150 ConstantRange CR2 = computeConstantRange(V, UseInstrInfo);
4151 ConstantRange::PreferredRangeType RangeType =
4152 ForSigned ? ConstantRange::Signed : ConstantRange::Unsigned;
4153 return CR1.intersectWith(CR2, RangeType);
4154}

4156OverflowResult llvm::computeOverflowForUnsignedMul(
4157 const Value *LHS, const Value *RHS, const DataLayout &DL,
4158 AssumptionCache *AC, const Instruction *CxtI, const DominatorTree *DT,
4159 bool UseInstrInfo) {
4160 KnownBits LHSKnown = computeKnownBits(LHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
4161 nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
4162 KnownBits RHSKnown = computeKnownBits(RHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
4163 nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
4164 ConstantRange LHSRange = ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(LHSKnown, false);
4165 ConstantRange RHSRange = ConstantRange::fromKnownBits(RHSKnown, false);
4166 return mapOverflowResult(LHSRange.unsignedMulMayOverflow(RHSRange));
4167}
4168
4169OverflowResult
4170llvm::computeOverflowForSignedMul(const Value *LHS, const Value *RHS,
4171 const DataLayout &DL, AssumptionCache *AC,
4172 const Instruction *CxtI,
4173 const DominatorTree *DT, bool UseInstrInfo) {
4174 // Multiplying n * m significant bits yields a result of n + m significant
4175 // bits. If the total number of significant bits does not exceed the
4176 // result bit width (minus 1), there is no overflow.
4177 // This means if we have enough leading sign bits in the operands
4178 // we can guarantee that the result does not overflow.
4179 // Ref: "Hacker's Delight" by Henry Warren
4180 unsigned BitWidth = LHS->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits();
4181
4182 // Note that underestimating the number of sign bits gives a more
4183 // conservative answer.
4184 unsigned SignBits = ComputeNumSignBits(LHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT) +
4185 ComputeNumSignBits(RHS, DL, 0, AC, CxtI, DT);
4186
4187 // First handle the easy case: if we have enough sign bits there's
4188 // definitely no overflow.
4189 if (SignBits > BitWidth + 1)
4190 return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
4191
4192 // There are two ambiguous cases where there can be no overflow:
4193 // SignBits == BitWidth + 1 and
4194 // SignBits == BitWidth
4195 // The second case is difficult to check, therefore we only handle the
4196 // first case.
4197 if (SignBits == BitWidth + 1) {
4198 // It overflows only when both arguments are negative and the true
4199 // product is exactly the minimum negative number.
4200 // E.g. mul i16 with 17 sign bits: 0xff00 * 0xff80 = 0x8000
4201 // For simplicity we just check if at least one side is not negative.
4202 KnownBits LHSKnown = computeKnownBits(LHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
4203 nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
4204 KnownBits RHSKnown = computeKnownBits(RHS, DL, /*Depth=*/0, AC, CxtI, DT,
4205 nullptr, UseInstrInfo);
4206 if (LHSKnown.isNonNegative() || RHSKnown.isNonNegative())
4207 return OverflowResult::NeverOverflows;
4208 }
4209 return OverflowResult::MayOverflow;
4210}
